{"title_page": "Raining Men (Rihanna song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Raining Men\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Rihanna]] featuring [[Nicki Minaj]]\n| album      = [[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]\n| released   = {{start date|2010|12|07}}\n| format     =\n| recorded   = 2010, Platinum Sound Recording Studios, [[Electric Lady Studios]] (New York City); Glenwood Recording Studios, ([[Burbank, California]])\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=44}}\n| label      = {{Flat list|\n*[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n*SRP}}\n| writer     = {{Flat list|\n*Melvin Hough II\n*Rivelino Wouter\n*Timothy Thomas\n*Theron Thomas\n*[[Nicki Minaj|Onika Maraj]]}}\n| producer   = {{Flat list|\n*Mel & Mus\n*[[Kuk Harrell]]}}\n| chronology = Rihanna\n| prev_title = [[All of the Lights]]\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title = [[S&M (song)|S&M]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Nicki Minaj\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[I Ain't Thru]]\n | prev_year  = 2010\n | title      = Raining Men\n | year       = 2010\n | next_title = [[Moment 4 Life]]\n | next_year  = 2010\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Raining Men'''\" is a song by Barbadian singer [[Rihanna]] from her fifth studio album, ''[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]'' (2010). Written by Melvin Hough II, Rivelino Wouter, Timothy Thomas, Theron Thomas and Onika Maraj, and produced by Mel & Mus, the song was sent to [[Urban contemporary|urban]] radio on December 7, 2010, as the album's third single in the United States, and was re-sent to urban radio on January 25, 2011. A [[hip hop music|hip hop]] song, it features rap vocals by [[Nicki Minaj]] and [[instrumentation]] consisting of [[Siren (noisemaker)|sirens]] and [[Bass (instrument)|bass]]. The song's lyrics revolve around how there is an endless supply of men available in the world. The song garnered a mixed response from [[Music journalism|music critics]]; some praised the chemistry between Rihanna and Minaj, while others commented that it bore strong resemblances to [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s song \"[[Diva (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Diva]]\" with regard to its composition, and were critical of the notion.\n\nUpon the release of ''Loud'', \"Raining Men\" charted on the singles charts in South Korea, the United Kingdom and the United States on the strength of [[Music download|digital download sales]]. In South Korea, the song peaked at number 41, while in the United Kingdom it peaked at number 142 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and number 31 on the [[UK R&B Chart]]. In the United States, it peaked at number 11 on the [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]], making this Rihanna's third single that failed to reach the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart (\"[[We Ride]]\", \"[[Wait Your Turn]]\"). Following the song's release to US urban radio, \"Raining Men\" peaked at number 48 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart. No [[music video]] was shot for the song, and it received no televised performances as part of promotion. The song was included on the [[set list]] of the [[Loud Tour]] (2011). The performance featured Rihanna in a [[Military camouflage|camouflage]] inspired outfit, accompanied by dancers in the same attire who held pink rifles.\n\n==Recording and production==\n[[File:MinajHammersteinBallroomNYC.jpg|thumb|upright|\"Raining Men\" received mixed reviews from critics, who praised the chemistry between Rihanna and [[Nicki Minaj]] (''pictured''), but criticized the song for failing to create anything new or original.]]\n\"Raining Men\" was written by Melvin Hough II, Rivelino Wouter, Timothy Thomas, Theron Thomas and [[Nicki Minaj]] (credited as Onika Maraj), with instrumental production of the song done by Mel & Mus.<ref name=\"CD notes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]|others=[[Rihanna]] |year=2010|type=liner notes |publisher=[[Def Jam Recordings]], SRP Records}}</ref> It features rap vocals by Minaj; Rihanna's and Minaj's vocals were recorded by [[Kuk Harrell]], Josh Gudwin, Marcos Tovar and Aerial Chobaz at Platinum Sound Recording Studios; [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]; [[Electric Lady Studios]], [[Greenwich Village]], New York City and Glenwood Recording Studios, [[Burbank, California|Burbank]], [[California]].<ref name=\"CD notes\"/> Koby Hass served as the assistant vocal recorder.<ref name=\"CD notes\"/> The song's music was recorded by Dana Nielsen, and was mixed by Jaycen Joshua.<ref name=\"CD notes\"/> Jesus Garnica served as the mixing assistant.<ref name=\"CD notes\"/>\n\n==Conception and development==\n\"Raining Men\" marked the second collaboration between Rihanna's and Minaj, the first being Minaj's song \"[[Fly (Nicki Minaj song)|Fly]]\", from her album ''[[Pink Friday]]'' (2010), on which Rihanna appeared as a guest vocalist.<ref name=\"PinkFridayNotes\">{{cite AV media notes|others=Nicki Minaj|title=[[Pink Friday]]|year=2010|type= inlay cover|publisher=[[Cash Money Records]], [[Young Money Entertainment]], [[Universal Republic Records]], [[Universal Motown]]|id=B0052WKZYC}}</ref> During an interview with [[Capital London|Capital FM]] radio station in London, England, Rihanna revealed that herself and Minaj had written songs together, specifically [[ballad]]s, for possible inclusion on the formers fourth studio album, ''[[Rated R (Rihanna album)|Rated R]]'' (2009), however none of the songs made the final track listing.<ref name=\"MTV1\">{{cite news|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1649780/rihanna-sings-praises-loud-collaborator-nicki-minaj.jhtml|title=Rihanna Sings Praises Of Loud Collaborator Nicki Minaj|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=October 12, 2010|accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref> Rihanna concluded her statement by saying that she could not wait to collaborate with the rapper again for her fifth studio album, the at the time unreleased and unnamed ''Loud''.<ref name=\"MTV1\"/> When questioned about what \"Raining Men\" was like, the singer stated that it is \"a really fun song. Nothing like the [[It's Raining Men|original]]. It's quite uptempo but kind of quirky and funny.\"<ref name=\"MTV1\"/>\n\nIn the same interview, Rihanna explained why she liked to collaborate with Minaj, saying \"She has a great buzz and she has a 'thing' to her. She is a star and that's why people love her. She's also really entertaining with her visual as well as her lyrics, and she has a great melody.\"<ref name=\"MTV1\"/> The singer continued to reveal how she was impressed with Minaj's songwriting abilities, saying \"I'm really amazed that she can write like that. [Nicki] not only raps but she can write songs too&nbsp;... It was really easy actually. We were going back and forth with the texts on how we were going to get to do it because we were in two different places and had two opposite schedules.\"<ref name=\"MTV1\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Copsey|first=Robert|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a281454/rihanna-nicki-minaj-collab-was-fun.html|title=Rihanna: 'Nicki Minaj collab was fun'|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=October 11, 2010|accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref> In an interview with DJ Semtex for [[BBC Radio]], Minaj explained how the concept for her rap verse developed, revealing \"I just wanted to be crazy, I wrote that track in bed actually. I had an off day, they sent me a record and said they needed it back in 24 hours and I wrote.\"<ref name=\"MTV2\">{{cite web|last=Crosley|first=Hilary|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/01/21/nicki-minaj-rihanna-raining-men-duet-written-in-bed/|title=Nicki Minaj Says 'Raining Men' Duet With Rihanna Was Written 'In Bed'|publisher=MTV|=|date=October 21, 2010|accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref> With regard to the original, \"[[It's Raining Men]]\", Minaj stated that she wanted to make \"Raining Men\" \"more melodic and crazy.\"<ref name=\"MTV2\"/> \"Raining Men\" was sent for [[Urban contemporary|urban]] radio adds as the third single from ''Loud'' on December 7, 2010.<ref name=\"UrbanRadioRelease2010\">{{cite magazine|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=12/07/2010&Format=5|title=R&R Going For Adds: Urban|magazine=[[Radio & Records]]|date=December 7, 2010|accessdate=April 30, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69spuYVCo?url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=12%2F07%2F2010&Format=5|archive-date=August 13, 2012}}</ref> On January 25, 2011, the song was re-released for urban radio adds.<ref name=\"UrbanRadioRelease2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases |title=January 23, 2011 |publisher=Allaccess.com |date=January 25, 2011 |accessdate=April 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110125155248/http://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases |archive-date=January 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Raining Men\" is a [[hip hop music|hip hop]] song,<ref name=\"MTV3\">{{cite news|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1651778/rihanna-dishes-on-nicki-minaj-collabos.jhtml|title=Rihanna Dishes On Nicki Minaj Collabos|publisher=MTV|=|date=November 11, 2010|accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> with a \"shiny trap beat\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Raining Men|magazine=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/02/best-rihanna-songs/raining-men|accessdate=November 25, 2014|publisher=Rich Antoniello}}</ref> that lasts for a duration of 3:44 (3 minutes, 44 seconds).<ref name=\"USiTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/loud/id458437339|title=iTunes - Music - Loud|work=[[iTunes Store]] (United States)|publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|date=August 18, 2011|accessdate=May 2, 2012}}</ref> The song is not a cover of [[The Weather Girls]] song \"It's Raining Men\", composed by [[Paul Jabara]] and [[Paul Shaffer]], however it is based on it with regard to its lyrical content and does sample it.<ref name=\"NYDailyNewsReview\">{{cite news|last=Farber|first=Jim|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/2010/11/16/2010-11-16_rihannas_loud_review_only_girl_in_the_world_trades_pain_for_carbonated_pleasure.html|title=Rihanna's 'Loud' review: Only girl in the world trades pain for carbonated pleasure|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York|date=November 16, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> [[Instrumentation]] consists of [[Siren (noisemaker)|sirens]] and  \"mind-melting\" [[Bass (instrument)|bass]].<ref name=\"SpinReview\">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Stacey|url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/rihanna-loud-def-jam|title=Rihanna, 'Loud' (Def Jam)|magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|publisher=[[SpinMedia]]|date=November 16, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> The song is written in the key of [[B-flat major|B\u266dmajor]] and is set in [[simple time]] with a moderated hip-hop [[Tempo|groove]], with a metronome of 80 [[Beats per minute#Beats per minute|beats per minute]].<ref name=\"Musicnotes\">{{cite journal|title=Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna 'Raining Men'|publisher=Musicnotes.com|id=MN0096703 (Product Number)|year=2010}}</ref> \"Raining Men{{\" '}}s composition was likened to the work of [[M.I.A. (artist)|M.I.A.]] by Emily McKay for ''[[NME]]''.<ref name=\"NMEReview\">{{cite web|last=Mackay|first=Emily|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/rihanna/11718|title=Rihanna \u2013 Album Review: Rihanna \u2013 Loud (Def Jam/Mercury) \u2013 Album Reviews|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]] ([[Time Inc.]])|date=November 12, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> Stacey Anderson for ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' commented on Minaj's vocal stylizaion of the word \"really,\" writing that she projects the word as a \"breathless contortion into its own fully demented sideshow,\" with regard to the fast speed in which Minaj raps.<ref name=\"SpinReview\"/> James Reed for ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' described Minaj's verse as a \"manic guest rhyme\".<ref name=\"BotonGlodeReview\">{{cite news|last=Reed|first=James|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/music/cd_reviews/articles/2010/11/15/on_loud_rihanna_explores_kink_and_drink_then_returns_to_the_dance_floor/|title=On 'Loud,' Rihanna explores kink and drink, then returns to the dance floor \u2013 The Boston Globe|work=[[Boston Globe]]|publisher=Christopher M. Mayer|date=November 15, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> Rihanna's [[vocal range]] in the song spans from the low note of [[G minor|G<sub>3</sub>]] to the high note of [[B\u266d (musical note)|B\u266d<sub>4</sub>]].<ref name=\"Musicnotes\"/> According to Jon Pareles for ''[[The New York Times]]'', the songs lyrics revolve around Rihanna and Minaj \"singing and rapping about an endless supply of available men.\"<ref name=\"NYTimesReview\">{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/16/arts/music/16choice.html?_r=1|title=Critics' Choice: New CDs|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, Jr.]]|date=2010-11-15|accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref> Lyrically, Kevin O'Donnell of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' described the song as Rihanna and Minaj's own \"female empowerment anthem.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=O'Donnell|first1=Kevin|title=Hear it: Rihanna and Nicki Minaj's Hot Duet|magazine=Spin|date=November 8, 2010|publisher=SpinMedia}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe song was met with mixed reviews from music critics. Jon Pareles and Jon Caramanica of ''The New York Times'' commented that \"Rihanna shares the mechanized, chattering beat of \"Raining Men\" with Nicki Minaj, singing and rapping about an endless supply of available men\".<ref name=\"NYTimesReview\"/> Stacey Anderson of ''Spin'' commented that the song is the highlight of the album, calling it \"a gloriously eccentric collaboration with Nicki Minaj that entwines their minor-key hyperventilating, air sirens dissolving into mind-melting bass, and the scene-stealing Minaj's breathless contortion of the simple word 'really' into its own fully demented sideshow\".<ref name=\"SpinReview\"/> [[BBC Music]] also commended Minaj's presence on the song, saying that \"Nicki Minaj makes for a superb partner in crime on Raining Men, her wild, kinetic flow complementing Rihanna\u2019s steely delivery to wicked effect\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Skinner|first=James|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/x5fd|title=Music \u2013 Review of Rihanna \u2013 Loud|publisher=[[BBC Music]]|date= November 15, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> Jim Farber for ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' said that \"Rihanna pairs just as well with Nicki Minaj, on a complete tear-down on the old Weather Girls disco standard 'It's Raining Men.' Here it's not a gay song of lust but a statement of assurance that no man should incite too much worry, considering their sheer numbers\".<ref name=\"NYDailyNewsReview\"/> Chris Richards of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' said that \"Nicki Minaj, a quick-witted rapper able to assume the voices of a dozen characters in a single song, fails to impart any wisdom on her colleague with \"Raining Men\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Richards|first=Chris|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/11/15/AR2010111506697.html|title=Rihanna's new albums: 'Loud,' yes, but what's clear?|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[Katharine Weymouth]]|date=November 16, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> Emily Mackay of ''NME'' said that \"Raining Men\" is a bold collaboration between Rihanna and Minaj, which plays to both of their strengths in the \"hip-pop\" collaboration.<ref name=\"NMEReview\"/>\n\nAugust Brown for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said that \"'Cheers (Drink to That)' and 'Raining Men,' as foamy and spunky as they may be, are such a dogleg turn from ''Rated R'' that they come off as little more than image recalibration. That's her prerogative as an artist, and it's certainly earned. But it underscores the one thing we've always wondered about Rihanna \u2014 what is she really feeling?\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Brown|first=August|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2010/11/album-review-rihannas-loud.html|title=Album review: Rihanna's 'Loud'|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 16, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> Ryan Dombal of [[Pitchfork Media]] was more critical of the song, commenting that \"Raining Men is a shameless Beyonc\u00e9 rip-off that would be quickly dismissed if not for the fact that it's a pretty-damn-good Beyonc\u00e9 rip off with a characteristically scene-stealing guest verse from Nicki Minaj\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Dombal|first=Ryan|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14897-loud/ |title=Album Reviews: Rihanna: Loud|work=[[Pitchfork Media]]|publisher=Ryan Schreiber|date=November 24, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> James Reed of ''The Boston Globe'' also noticed the similarity between the song's composition and the work of American [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] recording artist [[Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]], saying \"'Raining Men', borrowing a digitized riff from Beyonc\u00e9's 'Diva', features rising rapper Nicki Minaj on a typically manic guest rhyme. The song's message doubles as the album's mantra: Some cats really do have nine lives\".<ref name=\"BotonGlodeReview\"/> [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] reviewer Becky Bain praised Minaj's \"infectious and energetic verse\" and felt the song's rhythm \"fits Nicki's quirkiness perfectly\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bain|first1=Becky|title=It's \"Raining Men\" For Rihanna And Nicki Minaj|url=http://www.idolator.com/5680402/rihanna-nicki-minaj-its-raining-men|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]. SpinMedia|date=November 8, 2010|accessdate=November 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n[[File:Rihanna, LOUD Tour, Oakland 8.jpg|thumb|right|Rihanna performing \"Raining Men\" on the [[Loud Tour]] in Oakland, California.]]\nUpon the release of ''Loud'', \"Raining Men\" charted in South Korea, the United Kingdom and the United States on the strength of [[Music download|digital download sales]]. The song debuted at number 41 on the [[Gaon Chart|South Korea Gaon International Chart]] on November 14, 2010,<ref name=\"SouthKoreaDebut\">{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon?nationGbn=E|title=South Korea Gaon International Chart (Week: November 14, 2010 to November 20, 2010)|publisher=Gaon Chart|accessdate=February 6, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316222941/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon?nationGbn=E|archive-date=March 16, 2013|df=}}</ref> and fell to number 85 the following week before dropping out of the chart.<ref name=\"SouthKoreaSecond\">{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon?nationGbn=E|title=South Korea Gaon International Chart (Week: November 21, 2010 to November 28, 2010)|publisher=Gaon Chart|accessdate=2012-02-06|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316222941/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon?nationGbn=E|archive-date=March 16, 2013|df=}}</ref> It debuted and peaked at number 142 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] on November 27, 2010.<ref name=\"UKChart\">{{cite web|url=http://zobbel.de/cluk/101127cluk.txt|title=Chart Log UK: Chart entries update|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=November 27, 2011|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> The song was more successful on the [[UK R&B Chart]], where it peaked at number 30 in the same chart issue.<ref name=\"UKR&BDebut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/16/2010-11-27/|title=2010 Top 40 R&B Singles Archive - 27th November 2010|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=November 27, 2010|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> \"Raining Men\" peaked at number 11 on the US [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]], a component chart which represents the 25 songs which failed to make an impact on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart.<ref name=\"USBubbling\">{{cite web|title=Rihanna Chart History - Bubbling Under Hot 100|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=rihanna|chart=Bubbling Under Hot 100}}|work=Billboard|accessdate=December 2, 2011}}</ref> The song debuted at number 69 US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart for the week of December 25, 2010.<ref name=\"USR&BDebut\">{{cite web|title=Top Hip-Hop/R&B Songs - Week of December 25, 2010|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2010-12-25/r-b-hip-hop-songs?order=gainer|work=Billboard|date=December 25, 2010|accessdate=May 2, 2012}}</ref> It peaked at number 48 on the US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]].<ref name=\"RiRiR&BChartHis\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=rihanna|chart=R&B/Hip-Hop Songs}}|title=Rihanna Chart History - R&B/Hip Hop Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\n\"Raining Men\" was included on the [[set list]] of the [[Loud Tour]] in 2011.<ref name=\"Toronto\">{{cite web|last=Stevenson|first=Jane|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/06/07/rihanna-is-loud-sexy-and-larger-than-life|title=Rihanna is loud, sexy and larger than life|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=June 7, 2011|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> The performance featured Rihanna in a [[Military camouflage|camouflage]] inspired outfit, and was accompanied by dancers in the same attire who held pink rifles.<ref name=\"Toronto\"/> The set included a pink [[tank]] which was also present on the ''[[Rated R (Rihanna album)|Rated R]]'' supported tour, [[Last Girl on Earth Tour]] (2010/11).<ref name=\"Toronto\"/> It began with Rihanna appearing on stage sitting on the pink tank as it was wheeled from the back of the stage to the front while Minaj's rap verse played; Rihanna then concluded the song with her vocals.<ref name=\"Toronto\"/> \"Raining Men\" was preceded by \"[[Hard (Rihanna song)|Hard]]\" and \"Breakin' Dishes\", and featured the singer wearing the same outfit and set design.<ref name=\"Toronto\"/> Minaj has also performed her verse on her [[Pink Friday: Reloaded Tour]].\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Loud'', Def Jam Recordings, SRP Records.<ref name=\"LoudNotes\">{{cite AV media notes|title=[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]|date=November 12, 2010|others=[[Rihanna]]|type=Inlay cover|work=[[Def Jam Recordings]], SRP Records}}</ref>\n\n'''Recording'''\n*Vocal recording&nbsp;\u2013 Platinum Sound Recording Studios (New York City, NY); Electric Lady Recording Studios (New York City, NY); Glenwood Studios (Burbank, CA)\n*Music recording&nbsp;\u2013 Cahuenga Pass Studio (Los Angeles, CA)\n*Mixing&nbsp;\u2013 Larrabee Sound Studios (Los Angeles, CA)\n\n'''Personnel'''\n{{div col}}\n*Songwriting&nbsp;\u2013 Melvin Hough II, Rivelino Wouter, Timothy Thomas, Theron Thomas, Onika Maraj\n*Production&nbsp;\u2013 Mel & Mus\n*Vocal production and recording&nbsp;\u2013 Kuk Harrell, Josh Gudwin, Marcos Tovar, Aerial Chobaz\n*Assistant vocal production and recording&nbsp;\u2013 Koby Hass\n*Music recording&nbsp;\u2013  Dana Neilsen\n*Mixing&nbsp;\u2013 Jaycen Joshua\n*Assistant mixing&nbsp;\u2013 Jesus Garnica\n*Featured vocals&nbsp;\u2013 Nicki Minaj\n*Bathroom vocals&nbsp;\u2013 Theron Thomas \n{{div col end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2010-11)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| South Korea ([[Gaon Chart|Gaon]])<ref name=\"SouthKoreaDebut\"/>\n| align=center|41\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| UK R&B ([[UK R&B Chart|Official Charts Company]])<ref name=\"UKR&BDebut\"/>\n| align=center|30\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| UK Singles ([[UK Singles Chart|Official Charts Company]])<ref name=\"UKChart\"/>\n| align=center|142\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| US [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"USBubbling\"/>\n| align=center|11\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"RiRiR&BChartHis\"/>\n| align=center|48\n|}\n\n==Radio history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Country\n!scope=\"col\"|Date\n!scope=\"col\"|Format\n!scope=\"col\"|Label\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| United States\n| December 7, 2010<ref name=\"UrbanRadioRelease2010\"/>\n| [[Urban contemporary|Urban]] radio\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Def Jam Recordings]]\n|-\n| January 25, 2011<ref name=\"UrbanRadioRelease2011\"/>\n| Urban radio (re-release)\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Loud (Rihanna album)}}\n* [[Golconda (painting)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|rihanna|raining-men}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Rihanna songs}}\n{{Nicki Minaj singles}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2010 songs]]\n[[Category:Nicki Minaj songs]]\n[[Category:Rihanna songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Kuk Harrell]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Stargate (production team)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Nicki Minaj]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Theron Thomas]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Timothy Thomas]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings singles]]\n\n[[he:Loud#Raining Men]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Raining Men\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Rihanna]] featuring [[Nicki Minaj]]\n| album      = [[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]\n| released   = {{start date|2010|12|07}}\n| format     =\n| recorded   = Platinum Sound Recording Studios, [[Electric Lady Studios]] (New York City); Glenwood Recording Studios, ([[Burbank, California]])\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=44}}\n| label      = {{Flat list|\n*[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n*SRP}}\n| writer     = {{Flat list|\n*Melvin Hough II\n*Rivelino Wouter\n*Timothy Thomas\n*Theron Thomas\n*[[Nicki Minaj|Onika Maraj]]}}\n| producer   = {{Flat list|\n*Mel & Mus\n*[[Kuk Harrell]]}}\n| chronology = Rihanna\n| prev_title = [[All of the Lights]]\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title = [[S&M (song)|S&M]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Nicki Minaj\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[I Ain't Thru]]\n | prev_year  = 2010\n | title      = Raining Men\n | year       = 2010\n | next_title = [[Moment 4 Life]]\n | next_year  = 2010\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Raining Men'''\" is a song by Barbadian singer [[Rihanna]] from her fifth studio album, ''[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]'' (2010). Written by Melvin Hough II, Rivelino Wouter, Timothy Thomas, Theron Thomas and Onika Maraj, and produced by Mel & Mus, the song was sent to [[Urban contemporary|urban]] radio on December 7, 2010, as the album's third single in the United States, and was re-sent to urban radio on January 25, 2011. A [[hip hop music|hip hop]] song, it features rap vocals by [[Nicki Minaj]] and [[instrumentation]] consisting of [[Siren (noisemaker)|sirens]] and [[Bass (instrument)|bass]]. The song's lyrics revolve around how there is an endless supply of men available in the world. The song garnered a mixed response from [[Music journalism|music critics]]; some praised the chemistry between Rihanna and Minaj, while others commented that it bore strong resemblances to [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s song \"[[Diva (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Diva]]\" with regard to its composition, and were critical of the notion.\n\nUpon the release of ''Loud'', \"Raining Men\" charted on the singles charts in South Korea, the United Kingdom and the United States on the strength of [[Music download|digital download sales]]. In South Korea, the song peaked at number 41, while in the United Kingdom it peaked at number 142 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and number 31 on the [[UK R&B Chart]]. In the United States, it peaked at number 11 on the [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]], making this Rihanna's third single that failed to reach the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart (\"[[We Ride]]\", \"[[Wait Your Turn]]\"). Following the song's release to US urban radio, \"Raining Men\" peaked at number 48 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart. No [[music video]] was shot for the song, and it received no televised performances as part of promotion. The song was included on the [[set list]] of the [[Loud Tour]] (2011). The performance featured Rihanna in a [[Military camouflage|camouflage]] inspired outfit, accompanied by dancers in the same attire who held pink rifles.\n\n==Recording and production==\n[[File:MinajHammersteinBallroomNYC.jpg|thumb|upright|\"Raining Men\" received mixed reviews from critics, who praised the chemistry between Rihanna and [[Nicki Minaj]] (''pictured''), but criticized the song for failing to create anything new or original.]]\n\"Raining Men\" was written by Melvin Hough II, Rivelino Wouter, Timothy Thomas, Theron Thomas and [[Nicki Minaj]] (credited as Onika Maraj), with instrumental production of the song done by Mel & Mus.<ref name=\"CD notes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]|others=[[Rihanna]] |year=2010|type=liner notes |publisher=[[Def Jam Recordings]], SRP Records}}</ref> It features rap vocals by Minaj; Rihanna's and Minaj's vocals were recorded by [[Kuk Harrell]], Josh Gudwin, Marcos Tovar and Aerial Chobaz at Platinum Sound Recording Studios; [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]]; [[Electric Lady Studios]], [[Greenwich Village]], New York City and Glenwood Recording Studios, [[Burbank, California|Burbank]], [[California]].<ref name=\"CD notes\"/> Koby Hass served as the assistant vocal recorder.<ref name=\"CD notes\"/> The song's music was recorded by Dana Nielsen, and was mixed by Jaycen Joshua.<ref name=\"CD notes\"/> Jesus Garnica served as the mixing assistant.<ref name=\"CD notes\"/>\n\n==Conception and development==\n\"Raining Men\" marked the second collaboration between Rihanna's and Minaj, the first being Minaj's song \"[[Fly (Nicki Minaj song)|Fly]]\", from her album ''[[Pink Friday]]'' (2010), on which Rihanna appeared as a guest vocalist.<ref name=\"PinkFridayNotes\">{{cite AV media notes|others=Nicki Minaj|title=[[Pink Friday]]|year=2010|type= inlay cover|publisher=[[Cash Money Records]], [[Young Money Entertainment]], [[Universal Republic Records]], [[Universal Motown]]|id=B0052WKZYC}}</ref> During an interview with [[Capital London|Capital FM]] radio station in London, England, Rihanna revealed that herself and Minaj had written songs together, specifically [[ballad]]s, for possible inclusion on the formers fourth studio album, ''[[Rated R (Rihanna album)|Rated R]]'' (2009), however none of the songs made the final track listing.<ref name=\"MTV1\">{{cite news|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1649780/rihanna-sings-praises-loud-collaborator-nicki-minaj.jhtml|title=Rihanna Sings Praises Of Loud Collaborator Nicki Minaj|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=October 12, 2010|accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref> Rihanna concluded her statement by saying that she could not wait to collaborate with the rapper again for her fifth studio album, the at the time unreleased and unnamed ''Loud''.<ref name=\"MTV1\"/> When questioned about what \"Raining Men\" was like, the singer stated that it is \"a really fun song. Nothing like the [[It's Raining Men|original]]. It's quite uptempo but kind of quirky and funny.\"<ref name=\"MTV1\"/>\n\nIn the same interview, Rihanna explained why she liked to collaborate with Minaj, saying \"She has a great buzz and she has a 'thing' to her. She is a star and that's why people love her. She's also really entertaining with her visual as well as her lyrics, and she has a great melody.\"<ref name=\"MTV1\"/> The singer continued to reveal how she was impressed with Minaj's songwriting abilities, saying \"I'm really amazed that she can write like that. [Nicki] not only raps but she can write songs too&nbsp;... It was really easy actually. We were going back and forth with the texts on how we were going to get to do it because we were in two different places and had two opposite schedules.\"<ref name=\"MTV1\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Copsey|first=Robert|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a281454/rihanna-nicki-minaj-collab-was-fun.html|title=Rihanna: 'Nicki Minaj collab was fun'|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=October 11, 2010|accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref> In an interview with DJ Semtex for [[BBC Radio]], Minaj explained how the concept for her rap verse developed, revealing \"I just wanted to be crazy, I wrote that track in bed actually. I had an off day, they sent me a record and said they needed it back in 24 hours and I wrote.\"<ref name=\"MTV2\">{{cite web|last=Crosley|first=Hilary|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/01/21/nicki-minaj-rihanna-raining-men-duet-written-in-bed/|title=Nicki Minaj Says 'Raining Men' Duet With Rihanna Was Written 'In Bed'|publisher=MTV|=|date=October 21, 2010|accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref> With regard to the original, \"[[It's Raining Men]]\", Minaj stated that she wanted to make \"Raining Men\" \"more melodic and crazy.\"<ref name=\"MTV2\"/> \"Raining Men\" was sent for [[Urban contemporary|urban]] radio adds as the third single from ''Loud'' on December 7, 2010.<ref name=\"UrbanRadioRelease2010\">{{cite magazine|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=12/07/2010&Format=5|title=R&R Going For Adds: Urban|magazine=[[Radio & Records]]|date=December 7, 2010|accessdate=April 30, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69spuYVCo?url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=12%2F07%2F2010&Format=5|archive-date=August 13, 2012}}</ref> On January 25, 2011, the song was re-released for urban radio adds.<ref name=\"UrbanRadioRelease2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases |title=January 23, 2011 |publisher=Allaccess.com |date=January 25, 2011 |accessdate=April 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110125155248/http://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases |archive-date=January 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Raining Men\" is a [[hip hop music|hip hop]] song,<ref name=\"MTV3\">{{cite news|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1651778/rihanna-dishes-on-nicki-minaj-collabos.jhtml|title=Rihanna Dishes On Nicki Minaj Collabos|publisher=MTV|=|date=November 11, 2010|accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> with a \"shiny trap beat\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Raining Men|magazine=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/02/best-rihanna-songs/raining-men|accessdate=November 25, 2014|publisher=Rich Antoniello}}</ref> that lasts for a duration of 3:44 (3 minutes, 44 seconds).<ref name=\"USiTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/loud/id458437339|title=iTunes - Music - Loud|work=[[iTunes Store]] (United States)|publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|date=August 18, 2011|accessdate=May 2, 2012}}</ref> The song is not a cover of [[The Weather Girls]] song \"It's Raining Men\", composed by [[Paul Jabara]] and [[Paul Shaffer]], however it is based on it with regard to its lyrical content and does sample it.<ref name=\"NYDailyNewsReview\">{{cite news|last=Farber|first=Jim|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/2010/11/16/2010-11-16_rihannas_loud_review_only_girl_in_the_world_trades_pain_for_carbonated_pleasure.html|title=Rihanna's 'Loud' review: Only girl in the world trades pain for carbonated pleasure|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York|date=November 16, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> [[Instrumentation]] consists of [[Siren (noisemaker)|sirens]] and  \"mind-melting\" [[Bass (instrument)|bass]].<ref name=\"SpinReview\">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Stacey|url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/rihanna-loud-def-jam|title=Rihanna, 'Loud' (Def Jam)|magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|publisher=[[SpinMedia]]|date=November 16, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> The song is written in the key of [[B-flat major|B\u266dmajor]] and is set in [[simple time]] with a moderated hip-hop [[Tempo|groove]], with a metronome of 80 [[Beats per minute#Beats per minute|beats per minute]].<ref name=\"Musicnotes\">{{cite journal|title=Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna 'Raining Men'|publisher=Musicnotes.com|id=MN0096703 (Product Number)|year=2010}}</ref> \"Raining Men{{\" '}}s composition was likened to the work of [[M.I.A. (artist)|M.I.A.]] by Emily McKay for ''[[NME]]''.<ref name=\"NMEReview\">{{cite web|last=Mackay|first=Emily|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/rihanna/11718|title=Rihanna \u2013 Album Review: Rihanna \u2013 Loud (Def Jam/Mercury) \u2013 Album Reviews|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]] ([[Time Inc.]])|date=November 12, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> Stacey Anderson for ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' commented on Minaj's vocal stylizaion of the word \"really,\" writing that she projects the word as a \"breathless contortion into its own fully demented sideshow,\" with regard to the fast speed in which Minaj raps.<ref name=\"SpinReview\"/> James Reed for ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' described Minaj's verse as a \"manic guest rhyme\".<ref name=\"BotonGlodeReview\">{{cite news|last=Reed|first=James|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/music/cd_reviews/articles/2010/11/15/on_loud_rihanna_explores_kink_and_drink_then_returns_to_the_dance_floor/|title=On 'Loud,' Rihanna explores kink and drink, then returns to the dance floor \u2013 The Boston Globe|work=[[Boston Globe]]|publisher=Christopher M. Mayer|date=November 15, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> Rihanna's [[vocal range]] in the song spans from the low note of [[G minor|G<sub>3</sub>]] to the high note of [[B\u266d (musical note)|B\u266d<sub>4</sub>]].<ref name=\"Musicnotes\"/> According to Jon Pareles for ''[[The New York Times]]'', the songs lyrics revolve around Rihanna and Minaj \"singing and rapping about an endless supply of available men.\"<ref name=\"NYTimesReview\">{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/16/arts/music/16choice.html?_r=1|title=Critics' Choice: New CDs|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, Jr.]]|date=2010-11-15|accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref> Lyrically, Kevin O'Donnell of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' described the song as Rihanna and Minaj's own \"female empowerment anthem.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=O'Donnell|first1=Kevin|title=Hear it: Rihanna and Nicki Minaj's Hot Duet|magazine=Spin|date=November 8, 2010|publisher=SpinMedia}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe song was met with mixed reviews from music critics. Jon Pareles and Jon Caramanica of ''The New York Times'' commented that \"Rihanna shares the mechanized, chattering beat of \"Raining Men\" with Nicki Minaj, singing and rapping about an endless supply of available men\".<ref name=\"NYTimesReview\"/> Stacey Anderson of ''Spin'' commented that the song is the highlight of the album, calling it \"a gloriously eccentric collaboration with Nicki Minaj that entwines their minor-key hyperventilating, air sirens dissolving into mind-melting bass, and the scene-stealing Minaj's breathless contortion of the simple word 'really' into its own fully demented sideshow\".<ref name=\"SpinReview\"/> [[BBC Music]] also commended Minaj's presence on the song, saying that \"Nicki Minaj makes for a superb partner in crime on Raining Men, her wild, kinetic flow complementing Rihanna\u2019s steely delivery to wicked effect\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Skinner|first=James|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/x5fd|title=Music \u2013 Review of Rihanna \u2013 Loud|publisher=[[BBC Music]]|date= November 15, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> Jim Farber for ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' said that \"Rihanna pairs just as well with Nicki Minaj, on a complete tear-down on the old Weather Girls disco standard 'It's Raining Men.' Here it's not a gay song of lust but a statement of assurance that no man should incite too much worry, considering their sheer numbers\".<ref name=\"NYDailyNewsReview\"/> Chris Richards of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' said that \"Nicki Minaj, a quick-witted rapper able to assume the voices of a dozen characters in a single song, fails to impart any wisdom on her colleague with \"Raining Men\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Richards|first=Chris|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/11/15/AR2010111506697.html|title=Rihanna's new albums: 'Loud,' yes, but what's clear?|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[Katharine Weymouth]]|date=November 16, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> Emily Mackay of ''NME'' said that \"Raining Men\" is a bold collaboration between Rihanna and Minaj, which plays to both of their strengths in the \"hip-pop\" collaboration.<ref name=\"NMEReview\"/>\n\nAugust Brown for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said that \"'Cheers (Drink to That)' and 'Raining Men,' as foamy and spunky as they may be, are such a dogleg turn from ''Rated R'' that they come off as little more than image recalibration. That's her prerogative as an artist, and it's certainly earned. But it underscores the one thing we've always wondered about Rihanna \u2014 what is she really feeling?\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Brown|first=August|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2010/11/album-review-rihannas-loud.html|title=Album review: Rihanna's 'Loud'|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 16, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> Ryan Dombal of [[Pitchfork Media]] was more critical of the song, commenting that \"Raining Men is a shameless Beyonc\u00e9 rip-off that would be quickly dismissed if not for the fact that it's a pretty-damn-good Beyonc\u00e9 rip off with a characteristically scene-stealing guest verse from Nicki Minaj\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Dombal|first=Ryan|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14897-loud/ |title=Album Reviews: Rihanna: Loud|work=[[Pitchfork Media]]|publisher=Ryan Schreiber|date=November 24, 2010|accessdate=January 3, 2011}}</ref> James Reed of ''The Boston Globe'' also noticed the similarity between the song's composition and the work of American [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] recording artist [[Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles]], saying \"'Raining Men', borrowing a digitized riff from Beyonc\u00e9's 'Diva', features rising rapper Nicki Minaj on a typically manic guest rhyme. The song's message doubles as the album's mantra: Some cats really do have nine lives\".<ref name=\"BotonGlodeReview\"/> [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] reviewer Becky Bain praised Minaj's \"infectious and energetic verse\" and felt the song's rhythm \"fits Nicki's quirkiness perfectly\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bain|first1=Becky|title=It's \"Raining Men\" For Rihanna And Nicki Minaj|url=http://www.idolator.com/5680402/rihanna-nicki-minaj-its-raining-men|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]. SpinMedia|date=November 8, 2010|accessdate=November 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n[[File:Rihanna, LOUD Tour, Oakland 8.jpg|thumb|right|Rihanna performing \"Raining Men\" on the [[Loud Tour]] in Oakland, California.]]\nUpon the release of ''Loud'', \"Raining Men\" charted in South Korea, the United Kingdom and the United States on the strength of [[Music download|digital download sales]]. The song debuted at number 41 on the [[Gaon Chart|South Korea Gaon International Chart]] on November 14, 2010,<ref name=\"SouthKoreaDebut\">{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon?nationGbn=E|title=South Korea Gaon International Chart (Week: November 14, 2010 to November 20, 2010)|publisher=Gaon Chart|accessdate=February 6, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316222941/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon?nationGbn=E|archive-date=March 16, 2013|df=}}</ref> and fell to number 85 the following week before dropping out of the chart.<ref name=\"SouthKoreaSecond\">{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon?nationGbn=E|title=South Korea Gaon International Chart (Week: November 21, 2010 to November 28, 2010)|publisher=Gaon Chart|accessdate=2012-02-06|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316222941/http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon?nationGbn=E|archive-date=March 16, 2013|df=}}</ref> It debuted and peaked at number 142 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] on November 27, 2010.<ref name=\"UKChart\">{{cite web|url=http://zobbel.de/cluk/101127cluk.txt|title=Chart Log UK: Chart entries update|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=November 27, 2011|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> The song was more successful on the [[UK R&B Chart]], where it peaked at number 30 in the same chart issue.<ref name=\"UKR&BDebut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/16/2010-11-27/|title=2010 Top 40 R&B Singles Archive - 27th November 2010|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=November 27, 2010|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> \"Raining Men\" peaked at number 11 on the US [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]], a component chart which represents the 25 songs which failed to make an impact on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart.<ref name=\"USBubbling\">{{cite web|title=Rihanna Chart History - Bubbling Under Hot 100|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=rihanna|chart=Bubbling Under Hot 100}}|work=Billboard|accessdate=December 2, 2011}}</ref> The song debuted at number 69 US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart for the week of December 25, 2010.<ref name=\"USR&BDebut\">{{cite web|title=Top Hip-Hop/R&B Songs - Week of December 25, 2010|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2010-12-25/r-b-hip-hop-songs?order=gainer|work=Billboard|date=December 25, 2010|accessdate=May 2, 2012}}</ref> It peaked at number 48 on the US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]].<ref name=\"RiRiR&BChartHis\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=rihanna|chart=R&B/Hip-Hop Songs}}|title=Rihanna Chart History - R&B/Hip Hop Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\n\"Raining Men\" was included on the [[set list]] of the [[Loud Tour]] in 2011.<ref name=\"Toronto\">{{cite web|last=Stevenson|first=Jane|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/06/07/rihanna-is-loud-sexy-and-larger-than-life|title=Rihanna is loud, sexy and larger than life|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=June 7, 2011|accessdate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> The performance featured Rihanna in a [[Military camouflage|camouflage]] inspired outfit, and was accompanied by dancers in the same attire who held pink rifles.<ref name=\"Toronto\"/> The set included a pink [[tank]] which was also present on the ''[[Rated R (Rihanna album)|Rated R]]'' supported tour, [[Last Girl on Earth Tour]] (2010/11).<ref name=\"Toronto\"/> It began with Rihanna appearing on stage sitting on the pink tank as it was wheeled from the back of the stage to the front while Minaj's rap verse played; Rihanna then concluded the song with her vocals.<ref name=\"Toronto\"/> \"Raining Men\" was preceded by \"[[Hard (Rihanna song)|Hard]]\" and \"Breakin' Dishes\", and featured the singer wearing the same outfit and set design.<ref name=\"Toronto\"/> Minaj has also performed her verse on her [[Pink Friday: Reloaded Tour]].\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Loud'', Def Jam Recordings, SRP Records.<ref name=\"LoudNotes\">{{cite AV media notes|title=[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]|date=November 12, 2010|others=[[Rihanna]]|type=Inlay cover|work=[[Def Jam Recordings]], SRP Records}}</ref>\n\n'''Recording'''\n*Vocal recording&nbsp;\u2013 Platinum Sound Recording Studios (New York City, NY); Electric Lady Recording Studios (New York City, NY); Glenwood Studios (Burbank, CA)\n*Music recording&nbsp;\u2013 Cahuenga Pass Studio (Los Angeles, CA)\n*Mixing&nbsp;\u2013 Larrabee Sound Studios (Los Angeles, CA)\n\n'''Personnel'''\n{{div col}}\n*Songwriting&nbsp;\u2013 Melvin Hough II, Rivelino Wouter, Timothy Thomas, Theron Thomas, Onika Maraj\n*Production&nbsp;\u2013 Mel & Mus\n*Vocal production and recording&nbsp;\u2013 Kuk Harrell, Josh Gudwin, Marcos Tovar, Aerial Chobaz\n*Assistant vocal production and recording&nbsp;\u2013 Koby Hass\n*Music recording&nbsp;\u2013  Dana Neilsen\n*Mixing&nbsp;\u2013 Jaycen Joshua\n*Assistant mixing&nbsp;\u2013 Jesus Garnica\n*Featured vocals&nbsp;\u2013 Nicki Minaj\n*Bathroom vocals&nbsp;\u2013 Theron Thomas \n{{div col end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2010-11)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| South Korea ([[Gaon Chart|Gaon]])<ref name=\"SouthKoreaDebut\"/>\n| align=center|41\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| UK R&B ([[UK R&B Chart|Official Charts Company]])<ref name=\"UKR&BDebut\"/>\n| align=center|30\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| UK Singles ([[UK Singles Chart|Official Charts Company]])<ref name=\"UKChart\"/>\n| align=center|142\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| US [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"USBubbling\"/>\n| align=center|11\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"RiRiR&BChartHis\"/>\n| align=center|48\n|}\n\n==Radio history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Country\n!scope=\"col\"|Date\n!scope=\"col\"|Format\n!scope=\"col\"|Label\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| United States\n| December 7, 2010<ref name=\"UrbanRadioRelease2010\"/>\n| [[Urban contemporary|Urban]] radio\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Def Jam Recordings]]\n|-\n| January 25, 2011<ref name=\"UrbanRadioRelease2011\"/>\n| Urban radio (re-release)\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Loud (Rihanna album)}}\n* [[Golconda (painting)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|rihanna|raining-men}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Rihanna songs}}\n{{Nicki Minaj singles}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2010 songs]]\n[[Category:Nicki Minaj songs]]\n[[Category:Rihanna songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Kuk Harrell]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Stargate (production team)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Nicki Minaj]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Theron Thomas]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Timothy Thomas]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings singles]]\n\n[[he:Loud#Raining Men]]\n", "name_user": "2a01:e35:2e68:bca0:94b6:7219:f589:40ab", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raining_Men_(Rihanna_song)"}
{"title_page": "Complicated (Rihanna song)", "text_new": "{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Complicated\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[Rihanna]]\n| album    = [[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]\n| released = november 12, 2010\n| format   =\n| recorded = 2010; [[Westlake Recording Studios]], [[Larrabee Sound Studios]] (Los Angeles, California)\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = {{Flat list|\n*[[Dance-pop]]\n*[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n*[[Trance music|trance]]}}\n| length   = {{Duration|m=4|s=17}}\n| label    = {{Flat list|\n*[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n*SRP}}\n| writer   = {{Flat list|\n*[[Tricky Stewart]]\n*[[Ester Dean]]}}\n| producer = {{Flat list|\n*Tricky Stewart\n*Ester Dean\n*[[Kuk Harrell]]}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Complicated'''\" is a song by [[Barbadian people|Barbadian]] recording artist [[Rihanna]] from her fifth studio album ''[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]'' (2010). It was written and produced by [[Tricky Stewart]] and [[Ester Dean]]. \"Complicated\" is a [[dance-pop]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[trance music]] song, which also displays elements of [[Pop music|pop]], [[dance-pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]. It contains lyrical content explaining how two people in a relationship can find one another complicated at times. The song was acclaimed by critics, as the majority of reviewers concluded that it was one of the best tracks to be included on ''Loud''. Reviewers also praised Rihanna's vocal performance in the song. Upon the release of the album in November 2010, the song charted at number 50 on the [[Gaon Chart|South Korea Gaon International Chart]].\n\n==Background and inspiration==\n\"Complicated\" was written and produced by [[Tricky Stewart]] and [[Ester Dean]], for Rihanna's fifth studio album, ''Loud''. The song was recorded in 2010 at [[Westlake Recording Studios]], and [[Larrabee Sound Studios]], both located in [[Los Angeles, California]].<ref name=\"Album notes\"/> In an interview with Sway Calloway for [[MTV]], Rihanna explained the meaning behind \"Complicated\" and how it is applicable for both men and women, saying:\n\n{{quote|[Complicated is] not a sex thing. It's not like only women can sing this song or only women can relate to this song, 'cause it's an individual thing and sometimes, ''sometimes'' {{sic}} men are just too complicated and then again, men can find women complicated. But it all depends on the individual, because not all women think love is complicated and not all men think that, but there are some women and some men who strongly believe that love is just too complicated. Women, they're the first to say, 'It's your fault,' but most of the time it is [the man's] fault. But men are also great at turning that [shit] around on us and making us believe that we're wrong for something that we didn't even do. At the end of the day, love is [fucking] complicated.<ref name=\"ComplicatedMTVInterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1652326/rihanna-reveals-inspiration-loud-track-complicated.jhtml|title=Rihanna Reveals Inspiration For Loud's 'Complicated'|publisher=[[MTV]]. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|date=2010-11-16|accessdate=2012-01-13}}</ref>}}\n\n==Composition==\n{{Listen\n |filename     = Rihanna - Complicated.ogg\n |title        = Rihanna &ndash; \"Complicated\"\n |description  = A 20-second audio sample of the song.\n| pos          = right\n}}\n\"Complicated\" is [[dance-pop]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[trance music|trance]] song,<ref name=\"Gentry\">{{cite web|last=Gentry|first=Colin|url=http://www.4music.com/news/reviews/313/Rihanna-Loud-Review|title=News: Rihanna &mdash; Loud Review|website=[[4Music]]|date=2010-11-12|accessdate=2011-10-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120529072229/http://www.4music.com/news/reviews/313/Rihanna-Loud-Review|archivedate=May 29, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Mackay\">{{cite news|last=Mackay|first=Emily|url=http://www.nme.com/blog/index.php?blog=140&title=rihanna_loud_first_listen&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1|title=Rihanna, 'Loud' &mdash; Album First Listen|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|date=3 November 2010|accessdate=3 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321115455/http://www.nme.com/blog/index.php?blog=140&title=rihanna_loud_first_listen&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1|archive-date=21 March 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> which lasts for 4:17 (four minutes, 17 seconds).<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/loud/id458413837|title=iTunes - Music - Loud|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (US). [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> It also displays elements of [[Pop music|pop]], [[dance-pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]].<ref name=\"Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna Complicated\">{{cite journal|url=|title=Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna 'Complicated'|work=Musicnotes.com|publisher=[[Peer International (music publishing)|Peer International Music Publishing]]}}</ref> Emily Mackay of ''[[NME]]'' described the song as \"a clean, sharp dancepop number, backed by a dark and shuffling hip-hop beat.\"<ref name=\"Mackay\"/> According to the digital [[sheet music]] published by [[EMI]], \"Complicated\" is written in the [[key (music)|key]] of [[A minor]] and is set in [[common time]] with a moderate electro-ballad [[tempo|groove]].<ref name=\"Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna Complicated\"/> The instrumentation of \"Complicated\" consists of [[Synthesizer|synth]] beats and \"crackling outbursts\" of percussion and drums.<ref name=\"Pareles\">{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/16/arts/music/16choice.html|title=Critics' Choice: New CDs|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City|date=November 15, 2010|accessdate=October 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt also makes use of [[piano]] keys and [[guitar]] strings.<ref name=\"Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna Complicated\"/> Rihanna's vocal range in the song spans from the lower note of [[G (musical note)|G<sub>3</sub>]] to the higher note of [[C (musical note)|C<sub>5</sub>]].<ref name=\"Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna Complicated\"/> Mackay noted that the singer adopts a \"melancholic pop vocal\" for the duration of the song.<ref name=\"Mackay\"/> Chad Grischow of [[IGN]] stated that Rihanna appears to be screaming the vocals during the [[Hook (music)|hook]], citing the key of the \"jittery dance beat\" as the reason for [[oversinging]].<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web|last=Grischow|first=Chad|url=http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/113/1134952p1.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130104081541/http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/113/1134952p1.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 4, 2013|title=Rihanna: Loud Review|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[j2Global]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=November 16, 2010|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> However, Grischow commented that the singer sounds more pleasant to listen to during the [[Verse (music)#Verse|verses]], writing: \"The song actually sounds great when the light, plucky verses are quietly building to the hook, allowing her to sing rather than shout.\"<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Rihanna sings about the complications of a relationship,<ref name=\"ComplicatedMTVInterview\"/> as well as how the protagonist can experience [[mood swing]]s, whereby his or her feelings frequently change toward their lover.<ref name=\"Pareles\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"Complicated\" garnered critical acclaim from music critics. Colin Gentry of [[4Music]] named the song the highlight of the album, continuing to write that Rihanna pours her heart out to the listener as she sings about the intensity of her \"despair\".<ref name=\"Gentry\"/> Jon Parales of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described \"Complicated\" as being one of the more \"emotional\" songs on ''Loud''.<ref name=\"Pareles\"/> Emily Mackay of ''NME'' noted that the lyrics \"Why do you make it so hard to love you?/I hate it\" were reminiscent of songs by [[England|English]] pop [[girl group]], [[Sugababes]].<ref name=\"Mackay\"/> Steve Jones of ''[[USA Today]]'' observed that Rihanna's opinions of men are not just present on \"Complicated\", but rather that it is a recurring theme on ''Loud'', writing \"On more than one occasion, she makes it clear that she likes her men complicated and that they can expect her to be the same.\"<ref name=\"SteveJones\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Steve|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/2010-11-16-listen16_ST_N.htm|title=Listen Up: Rihanna is living out 'Loud' on new album |work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]], Inc.|date=2010-11-16|accessdate=2011-01-29}}</ref> Jones also listed it as one of his top songs to download from the album.<ref name=\"SteveJones\"/> Leah Greenblatt of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' commented that the \"spiraling dance-floor siren\" persona Rihanna adopted on the lead single from ''Loud'', \"[[Only Girl (In the World)]]\", was carried through onto \"Complicated\".<ref name=\"Greenblatt\">{{cite news|last=Greenblatt|first=Leah|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20440920,00.html|title=Loud &#124; Music|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]] division of [[Time Warner]]|date=2010-11-10|accessdate=2011-01-29}}</ref> Greenblatt continued to praise Rihanna's vocal performance, writing: \"Even while telling a recalcitrant man how hard he is to love, she sounds almost buoyant, her newly expanded vocals eager to scale the song's high-altitude house beat.\"<ref name=\"Greenblatt\"/>\n\nNima Baniamer of Contactmusic.com praised Rihanna's vocal performance and liked it to single track from ''Loud'', \"[[California King Bed]]\", writing: \"Taking a seat back from the thumping club classics, tracks like California King Bed and Complicated are both emotional singles that reveal Rihanna's surprisingly brilliant vocals.\"<ref name=\"ContactMusic\">{{cite web|last=Baniamer|first=Nima|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/album-review/rihanna-loud|title=Rihanna - Loud Album Review|publisher=[[Contactmusic.com]]|accessdate=2012-01-14}}</ref> Baniamer also expressed that it would be a \"travesty\" if the song was not chosen as a single from the album.<ref name=\"ContactMusic\"/> Genevieve Koski of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' was complimentary of the song, as well as single track \"[[What's My Name? (Rihanna song)|What's My Name?]]\", writing: \"Her bubbly patois and soaring divatronics elevate the generic R&B and Euro-dance flavors of 'What's My Name' and 'Complicated,' respectively.\"<ref name=\"AV\">{{cite news|last=Koski|first=Genevieve|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/rihanna-loud,48120/|title=Rihanna - Loud|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=The Onion, Inc.|date=2010-11-23|accessdate=2012-01-14}}</ref> However, Bill Lamb of [[About.com]] was critical of the song, labeling it as \"cluttered\" and the album's \"low-point\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamb|first=Bill|url=http://top40.about.com/od/albums/fr/Rihanna-Loud.htm|title=Rihanna \u2013 ''Loud''|work=[[About.com]]|publisher=The New York Times Company|accessdate=2012-01-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230002026/http://top40.about.com/od/albums/fr/Rihanna-Loud.htm|archive-date=2011-12-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n;Recording\n*Recorded at [[Westlake Recording Studios]], [[Los Angeles, California]] and Larrabee Sound Studios, Los Angeles, California.\n\n;Personnel\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*[[Songwriter|Songwriting]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Tricky Stewart|Christopher Stewart]], [[Ester Dean]]\n*[[Record producer|Production]]&nbsp;\u2013 Christopher Stewart, Ester Dean\n*Vocal engineering and recording&nbsp;\u2013 [[Kuk Harrell]], Josh Gudwin and Marcos Tovar\n*Music recording&nbsp;\u2013 Brian \"B-LUV\" Thomas & Andrew Wuepper\n{{col-2}}\n*Assistant vocal recording&nbsp;\u2013 Bobby Campbell\n*Mixing&nbsp;\u2013 Jaycen Joshua\n*Assistant mixing&nbsp;\u2013 Jesus Garnica\n{{col-end}}\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Loud'', [[Def Jam Recordings]], SRP Records.<ref name=\"Album notes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]|others=[[Rihanna]] |date=2010|type=liner notes |publisher=[[Def Jam Recordings]], SRP Records}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{{Wikipedia books|Loud (Rihanna album)}}\nUpon the release of ''Loud'', \"Complicated\" debuted and peaked at number 50 on the [[Gaon Chart|South Korea Gaon International Chart]] for the issue dated November 14, 2010.<ref name=\"SouthKoreaDebut\">{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon |title=South Korea Gaon International Chart (Week: November 14, 2010 to November 20, 2010) |publisher=Gaon Chart |date=2010-11-14 |accessdate=2012-01-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121219094524/http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon |archivedate=2012-12-19 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (2011)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Gaon Chart|South Korea Gaon International Chart]]<ref name=\"SouthKoreaDebut\"/>\n| 50\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|rihanna|complicated}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Rihanna songs}}\n\n[[Category:Rihanna songs]]\n[[Category:2011 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ester Dean]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tricky Stewart]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Tricky Stewart]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Kuk Harrell]]\n", "text_old": "{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Complicated\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[Rihanna]]\n| album    = [[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]\n| released =\n| format   =\n| recorded = 2010; [[Westlake Recording Studios]], [[Larrabee Sound Studios]] (Los Angeles, California)\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = {{Flat list|\n*[[Dance-pop]]\n*[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n*[[Trance music|trance]]}}\n| length   = {{Duration|m=4|s=17}}\n| label    = {{Flat list|\n*[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n*SRP}}\n| writer   = {{Flat list|\n*[[Tricky Stewart]]\n*[[Ester Dean]]}}\n| producer = {{Flat list|\n*Tricky Stewart\n*Ester Dean\n*[[Kuk Harrell]]}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Complicated'''\" is a song by [[Barbadian people|Barbadian]] recording artist [[Rihanna]] from her fifth studio album ''[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]'' (2010). It was written and produced by [[Tricky Stewart]] and [[Ester Dean]]. \"Complicated\" is a [[dance-pop]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[trance music]] song, which also displays elements of [[Pop music|pop]], [[dance-pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]. It contains lyrical content explaining how two people in a relationship can find one another complicated at times. The song was acclaimed by critics, as the majority of reviewers concluded that it was one of the best tracks to be included on ''Loud''. Reviewers also praised Rihanna's vocal performance in the song. Upon the release of the album in November 2010, the song charted at number 50 on the [[Gaon Chart|South Korea Gaon International Chart]].\n\n==Background and inspiration==\n\"Complicated\" was written and produced by [[Tricky Stewart]] and [[Ester Dean]], for Rihanna's fifth studio album, ''Loud''. The song was recorded in 2010 at [[Westlake Recording Studios]], and [[Larrabee Sound Studios]], both located in [[Los Angeles, California]].<ref name=\"Album notes\"/> In an interview with Sway Calloway for [[MTV]], Rihanna explained the meaning behind \"Complicated\" and how it is applicable for both men and women, saying:\n\n{{quote|[Complicated is] not a sex thing. It's not like only women can sing this song or only women can relate to this song, 'cause it's an individual thing and sometimes, ''sometimes'' {{sic}} men are just too complicated and then again, men can find women complicated. But it all depends on the individual, because not all women think love is complicated and not all men think that, but there are some women and some men who strongly believe that love is just too complicated. Women, they're the first to say, 'It's your fault,' but most of the time it is [the man's] fault. But men are also great at turning that [shit] around on us and making us believe that we're wrong for something that we didn't even do. At the end of the day, love is [fucking] complicated.<ref name=\"ComplicatedMTVInterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1652326/rihanna-reveals-inspiration-loud-track-complicated.jhtml|title=Rihanna Reveals Inspiration For Loud's 'Complicated'|publisher=[[MTV]]. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|date=2010-11-16|accessdate=2012-01-13}}</ref>}}\n\n==Composition==\n{{Listen\n |filename     = Rihanna - Complicated.ogg\n |title        = Rihanna &ndash; \"Complicated\"\n |description  = A 20-second audio sample of the song.\n| pos          = right\n}}\n\"Complicated\" is [[dance-pop]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[trance music|trance]] song,<ref name=\"Gentry\">{{cite web|last=Gentry|first=Colin|url=http://www.4music.com/news/reviews/313/Rihanna-Loud-Review|title=News: Rihanna &mdash; Loud Review|website=[[4Music]]|date=2010-11-12|accessdate=2011-10-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120529072229/http://www.4music.com/news/reviews/313/Rihanna-Loud-Review|archivedate=May 29, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Mackay\">{{cite news|last=Mackay|first=Emily|url=http://www.nme.com/blog/index.php?blog=140&title=rihanna_loud_first_listen&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1|title=Rihanna, 'Loud' &mdash; Album First Listen|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|date=3 November 2010|accessdate=3 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321115455/http://www.nme.com/blog/index.php?blog=140&title=rihanna_loud_first_listen&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1|archive-date=21 March 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> which lasts for 4:17 (four minutes, 17 seconds).<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/loud/id458413837|title=iTunes - Music - Loud|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (US). [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> It also displays elements of [[Pop music|pop]], [[dance-pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]].<ref name=\"Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna Complicated\">{{cite journal|url=|title=Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna 'Complicated'|work=Musicnotes.com|publisher=[[Peer International (music publishing)|Peer International Music Publishing]]}}</ref> Emily Mackay of ''[[NME]]'' described the song as \"a clean, sharp dancepop number, backed by a dark and shuffling hip-hop beat.\"<ref name=\"Mackay\"/> According to the digital [[sheet music]] published by [[EMI]], \"Complicated\" is written in the [[key (music)|key]] of [[A minor]] and is set in [[common time]] with a moderate electro-ballad [[tempo|groove]].<ref name=\"Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna Complicated\"/> The instrumentation of \"Complicated\" consists of [[Synthesizer|synth]] beats and \"crackling outbursts\" of percussion and drums.<ref name=\"Pareles\">{{cite news|last=Pareles|first=Jon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/16/arts/music/16choice.html|title=Critics' Choice: New CDs|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City|date=November 15, 2010|accessdate=October 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt also makes use of [[piano]] keys and [[guitar]] strings.<ref name=\"Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna Complicated\"/> Rihanna's vocal range in the song spans from the lower note of [[G (musical note)|G<sub>3</sub>]] to the higher note of [[C (musical note)|C<sub>5</sub>]].<ref name=\"Digital Sheet Music, Rihanna Complicated\"/> Mackay noted that the singer adopts a \"melancholic pop vocal\" for the duration of the song.<ref name=\"Mackay\"/> Chad Grischow of [[IGN]] stated that Rihanna appears to be screaming the vocals during the [[Hook (music)|hook]], citing the key of the \"jittery dance beat\" as the reason for [[oversinging]].<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web|last=Grischow|first=Chad|url=http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/113/1134952p1.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130104081541/http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/113/1134952p1.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 4, 2013|title=Rihanna: Loud Review|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[j2Global]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=November 16, 2010|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> However, Grischow commented that the singer sounds more pleasant to listen to during the [[Verse (music)#Verse|verses]], writing: \"The song actually sounds great when the light, plucky verses are quietly building to the hook, allowing her to sing rather than shout.\"<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Rihanna sings about the complications of a relationship,<ref name=\"ComplicatedMTVInterview\"/> as well as how the protagonist can experience [[mood swing]]s, whereby his or her feelings frequently change toward their lover.<ref name=\"Pareles\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"Complicated\" garnered critical acclaim from music critics. Colin Gentry of [[4Music]] named the song the highlight of the album, continuing to write that Rihanna pours her heart out to the listener as she sings about the intensity of her \"despair\".<ref name=\"Gentry\"/> Jon Parales of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described \"Complicated\" as being one of the more \"emotional\" songs on ''Loud''.<ref name=\"Pareles\"/> Emily Mackay of ''NME'' noted that the lyrics \"Why do you make it so hard to love you?/I hate it\" were reminiscent of songs by [[England|English]] pop [[girl group]], [[Sugababes]].<ref name=\"Mackay\"/> Steve Jones of ''[[USA Today]]'' observed that Rihanna's opinions of men are not just present on \"Complicated\", but rather that it is a recurring theme on ''Loud'', writing \"On more than one occasion, she makes it clear that she likes her men complicated and that they can expect her to be the same.\"<ref name=\"SteveJones\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Steve|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/2010-11-16-listen16_ST_N.htm|title=Listen Up: Rihanna is living out 'Loud' on new album |work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]], Inc.|date=2010-11-16|accessdate=2011-01-29}}</ref> Jones also listed it as one of his top songs to download from the album.<ref name=\"SteveJones\"/> Leah Greenblatt of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' commented that the \"spiraling dance-floor siren\" persona Rihanna adopted on the lead single from ''Loud'', \"[[Only Girl (In the World)]]\", was carried through onto \"Complicated\".<ref name=\"Greenblatt\">{{cite news|last=Greenblatt|first=Leah|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20440920,00.html|title=Loud &#124; Music|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]] division of [[Time Warner]]|date=2010-11-10|accessdate=2011-01-29}}</ref> Greenblatt continued to praise Rihanna's vocal performance, writing: \"Even while telling a recalcitrant man how hard he is to love, she sounds almost buoyant, her newly expanded vocals eager to scale the song's high-altitude house beat.\"<ref name=\"Greenblatt\"/>\n\nNima Baniamer of Contactmusic.com praised Rihanna's vocal performance and liked it to single track from ''Loud'', \"[[California King Bed]]\", writing: \"Taking a seat back from the thumping club classics, tracks like California King Bed and Complicated are both emotional singles that reveal Rihanna's surprisingly brilliant vocals.\"<ref name=\"ContactMusic\">{{cite web|last=Baniamer|first=Nima|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/album-review/rihanna-loud|title=Rihanna - Loud Album Review|publisher=[[Contactmusic.com]]|accessdate=2012-01-14}}</ref> Baniamer also expressed that it would be a \"travesty\" if the song was not chosen as a single from the album.<ref name=\"ContactMusic\"/> Genevieve Koski of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' was complimentary of the song, as well as single track \"[[What's My Name? (Rihanna song)|What's My Name?]]\", writing: \"Her bubbly patois and soaring divatronics elevate the generic R&B and Euro-dance flavors of 'What's My Name' and 'Complicated,' respectively.\"<ref name=\"AV\">{{cite news|last=Koski|first=Genevieve|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/rihanna-loud,48120/|title=Rihanna - Loud|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=The Onion, Inc.|date=2010-11-23|accessdate=2012-01-14}}</ref> However, Bill Lamb of [[About.com]] was critical of the song, labeling it as \"cluttered\" and the album's \"low-point\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamb|first=Bill|url=http://top40.about.com/od/albums/fr/Rihanna-Loud.htm|title=Rihanna \u2013 ''Loud''|work=[[About.com]]|publisher=The New York Times Company|accessdate=2012-01-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230002026/http://top40.about.com/od/albums/fr/Rihanna-Loud.htm|archive-date=2011-12-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n;Recording\n*Recorded at [[Westlake Recording Studios]], [[Los Angeles, California]] and Larrabee Sound Studios, Los Angeles, California.\n\n;Personnel\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*[[Songwriter|Songwriting]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Tricky Stewart|Christopher Stewart]], [[Ester Dean]]\n*[[Record producer|Production]]&nbsp;\u2013 Christopher Stewart, Ester Dean\n*Vocal engineering and recording&nbsp;\u2013 [[Kuk Harrell]], Josh Gudwin and Marcos Tovar\n*Music recording&nbsp;\u2013 Brian \"B-LUV\" Thomas & Andrew Wuepper\n{{col-2}}\n*Assistant vocal recording&nbsp;\u2013 Bobby Campbell\n*Mixing&nbsp;\u2013 Jaycen Joshua\n*Assistant mixing&nbsp;\u2013 Jesus Garnica\n{{col-end}}\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Loud'', [[Def Jam Recordings]], SRP Records.<ref name=\"Album notes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]|others=[[Rihanna]] |date=2010|type=liner notes |publisher=[[Def Jam Recordings]], SRP Records}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{{Wikipedia books|Loud (Rihanna album)}}\nUpon the release of ''Loud'', \"Complicated\" debuted and peaked at number 50 on the [[Gaon Chart|South Korea Gaon International Chart]] for the issue dated November 14, 2010.<ref name=\"SouthKoreaDebut\">{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon |title=South Korea Gaon International Chart (Week: November 14, 2010 to November 20, 2010) |publisher=Gaon Chart |date=2010-11-14 |accessdate=2012-01-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121219094524/http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon |archivedate=2012-12-19 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (2011)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Gaon Chart|South Korea Gaon International Chart]]<ref name=\"SouthKoreaDebut\"/>\n| 50\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|rihanna|complicated}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Rihanna songs}}\n\n[[Category:Rihanna songs]]\n[[Category:2011 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ester Dean]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tricky Stewart]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Tricky Stewart]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Kuk Harrell]]\n", "name_user": "2a01:e35:2e68:bca0:94b6:7219:f589:40ab", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complicated_(Rihanna_song)"}
{"title_page": "Let's Go Luna!", "text_new": "{{short description|Animated educational television series}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Let's Go Luna!\n| image                    = Let's Go Luna logo.png\n| genre                    = [[Children's television series]]<br />[[Educational]]<br />[[Comedy]]<br />[[Musical film|Musical]]\n| creator                  = [[Joe Murray (animator)|Joe Murray]]\n| writer                   = [[Peter Hannan (producer)|Peter Hannan]]<br />Mark Haslett<br />Rachel Lipman<br /> Joe Murray<br />'''Additional Writing By:'''<br />Tom Smith<br />Jackie Bae<br />Eric David Haddad<br />Dan Becker<br />Keith Silva<br />Ben Fossilman\n| director                 = Dave Brown<br>Steve Daye\n| voices                   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Judy Greer]]\n* [[Saara Chaudry]]\n* Jaiden Cannatelli\n* Aidan Wojtak-Hissong\n* Shayle Simons\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = Jeffrey Bernstein\n| opentheme                = \"Let's Go Luna, Let's Go!\"\n| endtheme                 = \"Let's Go Luna, Let's Go!\" (instrumental)\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Amin Bhatia (score)\n* Ari Posner (score)\n* Jeffrey Bernstein (songs)\n}}\n| country                  = {{Plainlist|\n* Canada\n* United States\n}}\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1<!-- increment as new seasons air -->\n| num_episodes             = 31<!-- increment as new episodes air -->\n| list_episodes            =\n| executive_producer       = Joe Murray<br />Vince Commisso\n| producer                 = Charley Thomas<br />'''Supervising Producers'''<br />Tanya Green<br />Julie Soebekti\n| editor                   =\n| runtime                  = 22 minutes\n| company                  = [[9 Story Media Group]]<br />[[Brown Bag Films]]<br />Joe Murray Productions<br />(uncredited)\n| distributor              = 9 Story International Distribution\n| network                  = [[PBS Kids]] (USA)<br />[[TVOKids]] (Canada)<br />[[Knowledge Kids]] (Canada)\n| picture_format           = [[720p]] ([[HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital]] 5.1\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2018|11|21}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = https://pbskids.org/luna\n| website_title            =\n| image_alt                =\n| caption                  =\n| channel                  =\n| first_run                =\n| released                 =\n| related                  = [[Rocko's Modern Life]]<br />[[Camp Lazlo]]<br />[[CatDog]]<br />[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]\n}}\n\n'''''Let's Go Luna!''''' is a Canadian-American flash-animated educational television series created by animator [[Joe Murray (animator)|Joe Murray]] (who previously created ''[[Rocko's Modern Life]]'' and ''[[Camp Lazlo]]'') and produced by [[Peter Hannan (producer)|Peter Hannan]]. It is co-produced by [[9 Story Media Group]]'s [[Brown Bag Films]] for [[PBS Kids]].<ref name=AM>{{cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/pbs-kids-gets-refreshed-ruff-ruffman-joe-murrays-luna-around-the-world/|title=PBS KIDS Gets Refreshed \u2018Ruff Ruffman,\u2019 Joe Murray\u2019s \u2018Luna Around the World\u2019|author=Mercedes Milligan|work=[[Animation Magazine]]|date=July 31, 2017|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> [[Judy Greer]] provides the voice of the titular Luna.<ref name=\"Greer\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/05/lets-go-luna-judy-greer-pbs-kids-new-series-1202385936/|title=\u2018Let\u2019s Go Luna!\u2019: Judy Greer Leads Voice Cast For New PBS Kids Series \u2013 Watch An Exclusive Clip|author=Erik Pedersen|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 9, 2018|access-date=May 10, 2018}}</ref> It is confirmed that there will be 38 half-hour episodes and a one-hour special.<ref name=AM/> Each episode consists of two 11-minute story segments,<ref name=\"Greer\" /> with a short segment of either Andy, Carmen or Leo telling a folktale, song or poem from that country in between.\n\n==Premise==\n''Let's Go Luna!'' set in a world populated by [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] animals, focuses on three kids-- Leo, a [[wombat]]<!-- From https://www.pbs.org/parents/shows/luna \"Let's Go Luna! follows the adventures of three friends \u2013 Andy, a wombat from Australia...\" Changes from this to dog should be considered vandalism--> from [[Australia]], Andy, a [[frog]] from the [[United States]] and Carmen, a [[butterfly]] from [[Mexico]]-- who travel around the world with their parents' traveling [[circus|performance troupe]] \"Circo Fabuloso.\" Along their stops, Luna the [[Moon]], depicted about {{convert|5|ft|m}} tall with arms, legs and a face, and wearing a straw hat and red boots, occasionally comes down to Earth to teach them about local languages, music, food, and other customs. Two half-hour episodes, consisting of two segments each and four in total, take place in a single country where the gang stop at, learn about and meet friends around the world. With a team of cultural anthropologists on board, ''Let's Go Luna!'' is \"meticulously researched to ensure cities and regions are authentically and respectfully portrayed.\"<ref name=GPB>{{cite web|url=http://www.gpb.org/blogs/education-matters/2018/11/15/new-pbs-kids-show-lets-go-luna-takes-children-around-the-world|title=PBS KIDS Gets Refreshed \u2018Ruff Ruffman,\u2019 Joe Murray\u2019s \u2018Luna Around the World\u2019|author=Mary Anne Lane\n|work=[[Georgia Public Broadcasting]]|date=November 15, 2018|access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\n===Main===\n* Luna (voiced by [[Judy Greer]]), the moon, who guides Leo, Andy and Carmen on their trips during the daytime. Luna knows every person in the world and has magical capabilities.\n* Leo Chockers (voiced by Aidan Wojtak-Hissong (2018) and Shayle Simons (2018-present)), a 7-year-old [[wombat]] from [[Sydney]], Australia who loves food and is learning to become a cook like his father.\n* Andy Hopper (voiced by Jaiden Cannatelli (2018-2020) and Evan O'Donnell (2020)), a 7-year-old frog from the United States who loves art.\n* Carmen Mariposa (voiced by [[Saara Chaudry]]), a 7-year-old [[butterfly]] from [[Mexico City]], Mexico who plays a Spanish guitar handed down from her deceased grandmother.\n* Magic Globe (voiced by Miku Graham), a miniature globe of the world that lives in Carmen's pocket and can share information about the places the children visit.\n\n===Recurring===\n* Se\u00f1or Moncarlo Fabuloso (voiced by [[Paul Braunstein]]), a [[flamingo]] from [[Barcelona]], Spain and the ringmaster of Circo Fabuloso.\n* Honey (voiced by Zoe Hatz), Carmen's mischievous yellow pet [[hamster]]. She often escapes from her cage but it is only because she is curious and wishes to be included.\n* Mr. Hockbar (voiced by [[David Berni]]), a [[lizard]] who does odd jobs.\n* Maria Mariposa (voiced by Tamara Almeida), Carmen's single mother and conductor of the Circo Fabuloso Band.\n* Wolfgang Chockers (voiced by [[Paul Braunstein]]), Leo\u2019s father and the Circo's resident chef.\n* Pippa Chockers (voiced by [[Linda Ballantyne]]), Leo\u2019s mother and the Circo's carpenter.\n* Mathilda Chockers, Leo's baby sister.\n* Lucie Hopper (voiced by Carolyn Scott), Andy\u2019s mother and the Circo's costume designer.\n* Sam Hopper (voiced by [[Dan Chameroy]]), Andy\u2019s father and the Circo's prop-maker.\n* Bonjour and Au Revoir (voiced by Peter Cugno), twin [[mandrill]] brothers from [[Paris]], France who work as clowns.\n* Ingrid Svenson-Benson (voiced by Brigitte Solem), a centipede from Sweden and the Circo\u2019s contortionist.\n* Salami Strong (voiced by [[Paul Braunstein]]), an alligator from Italy and the Circo\u2019s strongman.\n* Pablo (voiced by [[Cory Doran]]), an [[armadillo]] from [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil, who performs with the Melvinis, a group of six living [[bowling pins]].\n* The Acronauts, a trio of acorn shaped bears.\n\n===Guest Stars===\n* Viktorya and Boris Durov (voiced by Yana Gold and Adrian Jaworski), juggling bears from Russia\n* Fong (voiced by Owen Kwong)\n* Pico (voiced by Leonidas Castrounis), Carmen's armadillo friend from Mexico City.\n* David (voiced by [[Robert Tinkler]])\n* Oscar (voiced by Wyatt White)\n* Aman (voiced by Saad Siddiqui)\n* Kilasuw (voiced by Alex Hatz)\n* Alisa (voiced by [[Stacey DePass]])\n* Loe (voiced by Zharah Sdoherta)\n* Iki (voiced by Julie Gadsdan)\n* Nathin (voiced by Kiwaliu Daretyou)\n* Timur (voiced by Alex Hatz), a firefighter from Istanbul.\n* Oliye (voiced by Ortkiu Yteadegrah (uncredited))\n* Hikloei (voiced by Laaibah Alvi)\n* Silas (voiced by Ryan Allen), an ostrich elephant caretaker from Nairobi.\n* Mukandi (voiced by Malube Uhindu-Gingala)\n* Dexter (voiced by Jim Codrington), a greyhound known for his expert in music. \n* Remy (voiced by Joey Nijem)\n* Skye (voiced by Bryn McCauley), a red fox from Juneau.\n* Gina (voice by Samantha Weinstein)\n\n==Episodes==\n===Season 1 (2018-present)===\n{{Episode table\n| background = #3198FF\n| overall =\n| title =\n| writer =\n| aux2 =\n| aux2T = Storyboard and additional writing by\n| aux3 =\n| aux3T = Location\n| airdate =\n| airdateT = Original air date\n| episodes =\n\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 1\n| Title = What's the Big Idea?\"<hr>\"The Day of the Dead\n| WrittenBy = [[Peter Hannan (producer)|Peter Hannan]] & Eric David Haddad<hr>Peter Hannan\n| Aux2 = Dan Becker<hr>Tom Smith & Jackie Bae\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|11|21}}<br>{{Start date|2019|05|05}} (Canada)\n| Aux3 = [[Mexico City]], [[Mexico]]\n| ShortSummary = In [[Mexico City]], Andy learns about [[Mexican muralism|murals]] when trying to find something to paint on.<hr>Carmen must face her fear of skeletons in order to make it to her Grandmother's [[Day of the Dead]] altar.\n| LineColor = 3198FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 2\n| Title = Hola Mariachi!\"<hr>\"Loco for Cocoa\n| WrittenBy = [[Joe Murray (animator)|Joe Murray]] & Luccy Baillie<hr>Joe Murray & Mark Haslett\n| Aux2 = Tom Smith & Jackie Bae<hr>Dan Becker & Eric David Haddad\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|11|21}}<br>{{Start date|2019|05|04}} (Canada)<hr>{{Start date|2018|11|22}}<br>{{Start date|2019|05|04}} (Canada)\n| Aux3 = [[Mexico City]], [[Mexico]]\n| ShortSummary = Carmen tries to find a [[Mariachi]] band to fill in for the Circo's band when they get the hiccups.<hr>The trio help Carmen's friend Pico deliver a lost cocoa bean that was accidentally left behind by his mother.\n| LineColor = 3198FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 3\n| Title = You Froze My Shorts\"<hr>\"What a Matryoshka\n| WrittenBy = Mark Haslett<hr>Peter Hannan\n| Aux2 = Dan Becker & Eric David Haddad<hr>Tom Smith & Jackie Bae\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|11|21}}<hr>{{Start date|2018|11|27}}\n| Aux3 = [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n| ShortSummary = Luna shows the kids different ways to stay warm during a Russian winter.<hr>A delivery mix-up tasks the kids with returning a giant [[matryoshka doll]] to the store.\n| LineColor = 3198FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 4\n| Title = Lullaby for Baby Vlad\"<hr>\"Space Is the Place\n| WrittenBy = Rachel Lipman<hr>Joe Murray\n| Aux2 = Dan Becker & Eric David Haddad<hr>Tom Smith & Jackie Bae\n| Aux3 = [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|11|22}}<br>{{Start date|2019|05|11}} (Canada)\n| ShortSummary = Leo and Andy watch over a cranky baby bear named Vlad while Luna and Carmen search for a lullaby called \"Bayushki Bayu\" to help him go to sleep.<hr>Andy's love for space is fulfilled by a trip to a [[Memorial Museum of Cosmonautics|Russian space museum]].\n| LineColor = 3198FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 5\n| Title = Bob the Plant\"<hr>\"Aren't We a Pair?\n| WrittenBy = Joe Murray<hr>Mark Haslett\n| Aux2 = Dan Becker & Eric David Haddad <hr>Tom Smith & Jackie Bae\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|11|21}}<hr>{{Start date|2018|11|28}}\n| Aux3 = [[Cairo]], [[E