on owns managing and merchandising rights to the show outside Canada.<ref name=DL>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/07/pbs-kids-luna-around-the-world-animated-series-tca-1202138864/amp/|title=PBS Kids Greenlights \u2018Luna Around The World\u2019 Animated Series \u2013 TCA|author=Denise Petski|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 30, 2017|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> It is also one of a few shows for preschoolers and PBS' first storyboard-driven show where storyboard artists work with the writers, in order to create \"visually-driven narratives that highlight each city's distinctive landscape and features.\"<ref name=GPB/>\n\n==Reception==\n''Let's Go Luna'' has received generally positive reviews from television critics and parents of young children. ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote, \"Teaching tolerance, kindness and friendship.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/what-to-watch-with-your-kids-lets-go-luna-kung-fu-panda-the-paws-of-destiny-and-more/2018/11/28/ef98cd0c-f01d-11e8-96d4-0d23f2aaad09_story.html|title=What to watch with your kids: \u2018Let\u2019s Go Luna!,\u2019 \u2018Kung Fu Panda: The Paws of Destiny\u2019 and more|last=|first=|date=November 29, 2018|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==International broadcast==\nThe show airs on [[Nat Geo Kids (Latin American TV channel)|Nat Geo Kids]] in Latin America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kidscreen.com/2018/11/14/nat-geo-kids-snaps-up-three-shows-from-9-story/|title=Nat Geo Kids snaps up three shows from 9 Story\n|author=Alexander Whyte|work=Kidscreen|date=November 14, 2018|access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> In [[Spain]], the show airs on [[Canal Panda (Spain)|Canal Panda]]. In [[Canada]], the show airs on [[TVOKids]]. In the half-hour broadcast of Let's Go Luna on TVOKids, the short segment that occurs between the two 11-minute story segments of the show is kept in the broadcast instead of being removed.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Canada|United States|Television}}\n* [https://pbskids.org/luna Official website]\n* {{IMDb title|id=tt7200884}}\n\n{{Joe Murray}}\n{{PBS Kids shows}}\n\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s Canadian animated television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2020s Canadian animated television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated musical television series]]\n[[Category:American flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:American preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:Anthropomorphic animals]]\n[[Category:Canadian animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's animated musical television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:PBS Kids shows]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about frogs and toads]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about insects]]\n[[Category:Fictional butterflies and moths]]\n[[Category:Fictional wombats]]\n[[Category:Television series about the Moon]]\n[[Category:Television series by 9 Story Media Group]]\n[[Category:Television series by Brown Bag Films]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Joe Murray]]\n[[Category:2018 Canadian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2018 American television series debuts]]\n", "name_user": "HalfShadow", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Let%27s_Go_Luna!"}
{"title_page": "Willa Brown", "text_new": "{{short description|American aviator, educator, activist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Willa Brown\n|image       = \"Willa Beatrice Brown, a 31-year-old Negro American, serves her country by training pilots for the U.S. Army Air Forces. - NARA - 535717.jpg\n|alt         =\n|caption     = Brown as a lieutenant in the [[United States Civil Air Patrol]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|mf=yes|1906|01|22}}\n|birth_place = [[Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1992|07|18|1906|01|22}}\n|death_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|other_names =\n|known_for   = [[Civil rights]] leader<br/>First female African American pilot licensed in the United States<br/>First African American officer in the United States Civil Air Patrol<br/>First African American woman to run for [[United States Congress]]\n|occupation  = [[Pilot (aeronautics)|Pilot]], [[Lobbyist]], [[Activist]], [[Teacher]]\n|spouse   = {{Marriage|Wilbur Hardaway|November 24, 1929|1931|div}}<br>{{Marriage|[[Cornelius Coffey]]|1939|end=div}}{{efn|Most sources give the date of their marriage as 1939, but <ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> gives the date as 1947 and indicates that there is no record of them marrying in 1939.}}<br>{{Marriage|Rev. J. H. Chappell|1955}}\n}}\n'''Willa Beatrice Brown''' (January 22, 1906 \u2013 July 18, 1992) was an American [[Pilot (aeronautics)|aviator]], [[lobbyist]], [[teacher]], and [[Civil Rights Movement|civil rights]] activist.<ref name=\"anb\">{{cite web |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |title=Brown, Willa (1906-1992), pilot and aviation educator |url=http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01864.html |website=American National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en| url-access=subscription}}</ref> She was the first [[African American]] woman to earn a pilot's license in the United States,<ref name=\"blackpast\">{{Cite web|title = Brown, Willa B. (1906\u20131992) |url = http://www.blackpast.org/aah/brown-willa-b-1906-1992|website = The Black Past|author=Davis, Edmond|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref> the first African American woman to run for the [[United States Congress]], first African American officer in the [[Civil Air Patrol]], and first woman in the U.S. to have both a pilot's license and an aircraft mechanic's license.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"DOM\"/> She was a lifelong advocate for gender and racial equality in the field of aviation as well as in the military. She not only lobbied the U.S. government to integrate the [[United States Army Air Corps]] and include African Americans in the Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), but also co-founded the [[Coffey School of Aeronautics]] with [[Cornelius Coffey]], the first private flight training academy owned and operated by African Americans in the U.S. She trained hundreds of pilots, several of whom went on to become [[Tuskegee Airmen]]; the creation of which has been credited to Brown's lobbying efforts. <ref>{{Cite web|title = Our History {{!}} 99s in Aviation History {{!}} Women in Aviation |first=Kelli|last=Grant|url = http://www.ninety-nines.org/women-in-aviation-article.htm|website = The Ninety-Nines, Inc.|access-date =February 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\">{{cite web | title=Willa Brown Chappell | website=kchr.ky.gov | date=2020-03-31 | url=https://kchr.ky.gov/ggbk/Pages/gbk33.aspx | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBrown remained politically and socially active in [[Chicago]] long after the Coffey School closed in 1945. She organized flight schools for children, ran in Congressional primary elections in 1946 and 1950, was an active member of the Westside Community Church, and taught in the Chicago Public School System until 1971, when she retired at age 65.\n\n== Early life ==\nWilla Beatrice Brown was born to Reverend and Mrs. Erice B. Brown on January 22, 1906, in [[Glasgow, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"blackpast\"/> She graduated from Wiley High School in Terra Haute, Indiana, and attended [[Indiana State University|Indiana State Teachers College]] where she graduated in 1927 with a bachelor's degree. Ten years later she earned an [[M.B.A.]] from [[Northwestern University]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Black Women in America: An Historical Encyclopedia|year=1994|publisher=Indiana University Press | location= Bloomington |isbn=0-253-32774-1 | pages=184\u2013185 | chapter=Brown, Willa Beatrice (1906\u20131992)|first=Elizabeth Hadley|last=Freydberg}}</ref><ref name=\"Davis 2012\">{{cite web | last=Davis | first=Edmond | title=Willa B. Brown (1906-1992) | website=BlackPast | date=2012-07-25 | url=https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/brown-willa-b-1906-1992/ | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBrown taught in [[Gary, Indiana]] at [[Emerson High School (Indiana)|Emerson High School]]'s [[Theodore Roosevelt College and Career Academy#History|Roosevelt Annex]] from 1927 to 1932.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/><ref name=\"Davis 2012\"/> She then moved to Chicago, where she worked in a variety of jobs, including secretarial work, social work, and teaching.<ref name=\"notable-black-american-women\">{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Jessie Carney |title=Notable Black American women |publisher=Gale Research |isbn=978-0810391772 |pages=69\u201371}}</ref> In 1934, she met [[John C. Robinson]], who introduced her to the Challenger Air Pilots Association, a group of African American pilots.<ref name=\"anb\" />\n\n== Aviation career ==\n[[File:Young Willa Brown.jpg|thumb|left|Willa Brown as a young woman, standing on an airfield]]\nIn 1934, Brown began studying at Chicago's racially segregated Harlem Field with [[Cornelius Coffey]], a certified flight instructor and expert aviation mechanic. She was one of few women who attended [[Curtiss\u2013Wright Aeronautical University]] where she studied aircraft maintenance and earned an aircraft mechanic's license in 1935.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\">{{cite book |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |last2=Sawyer |first2=Miriam |last3=Fannin |first3=Caroline |title=Distinguished African Americans in aviation and space science |publisher=Oryx Press |isbn=978-1573562461 |pages=49\u201352|location=Westport, Conn.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/distinguishedafr00gube}}</ref><ref name=\"DOM\">{{cite web | title=Masterful Willa Brown (1906-1992) | website=DOM Magazine | date=2010-01-01 | url=https://dommagazine.com/article/masterful-willa-brown-1906-1992 | access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> She earned a private pilot's license in 1938<ref>{{cite news |title=YOUNG WOMAN FLYER GETS PILOT'S LICENSE: Willa Brown, Chicago Aviatrix, Can Carry Passengers, Give Instructions or Make Cross-Country Flights |work=The Pittsburgh Courier |date=2 July 1938 |page=11}}</ref> and a commercial pilot's license in 1939, becoming the first African American woman to earn either type of license in the United States.<ref name=\"anb\" /><ref name=\"chicago-tribune\">{{cite news |title=Chicago and the Tuskegee Airmen |work=Chicago Tribune |date=January 19, 2015 | location=Sec. 1 |page=14 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/opinion/editorials/ct-tuskegee-airmen-chicago-world-war-ii-willa-brown-edit-0119-jm-20150119-story.html}}</ref>{{efn|[[Bessie Coleman]] was the first black American, male or female, to earn an international pilot's license which she obtained in France in the 1920s, whereas Brown was the first black American woman to earn a pilot's license in the U.S.; see <ref name=DOM/>, <ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\" />, <ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" /> and <ref name=\"Dawson Bowles 2005 p. 5\">{{cite book | last=Dawson | first=V.P. | last2=Bowles | first2=M.D. | title=Realizing the Dream of Flight: Biographical Essays in Honor of the Centennial of Flight, 1903-2003 | publisher=National Aeronautics and Space Administration, NASA History Division, Office of External Relations | series=NASA SP | year=2005 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NpIpJI7nYV4C&pg=PA5 | access-date=2020-04-05 | page=5}}</ref>}}\n\nWilla Brown, Cornelius Coffey and Enoch P. Waters worked together to form the National Negro Airmen Association of America, later renamed to National Airmen's Association of America which was incorporated in 1939. Their primary mission was to attract more interest in aviation, help develop a better understanding in the field of aeronautics and pursue more African American participation in both fields.<ref name=\"Lest We Forget 1939\">{{cite web | title=NATIONAL AIRMEN ASSOCIATION OF AMERICA ...before the Tuskegee Airmen :: World War II :: Tuskegee Airmen :: Lest We Forget | website=Lest We Forget | date=1939-08-16 | url=http://lestweforget.hamptonu.edu/page.cfm?uuid=9FEC42B7-EB34-45CE-CC673CA72120E420 | access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> As the organization's national secretary and president of the Chicago branch, Brown became an activist for racial equality. Later, she and Coffey married and established the Coffey School of Aeronautics at Harlem Airport in Chicago, where they trained black pilots and aviation mechanics.<ref name=\"cap-bio\">{{cite web |last1=Montague |first1=Carlos |title=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |url=https://www.cap.news/willa-brown-pioneer-for-female--african-american-aviation/ |website=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n[[File:LIEUT. WILLA BROWN - AVIATRIX-MAKER OF PILOTS - NARA - 535627.tif|thumb|Office for Emergency Management publication featuring Brown]]\nShe lobbied the government continuously, advocating for integration of black pilots into a then-segregated Army Air Corps and federal [[Civilian Pilot Training Program]] (CPTP), the latter of which was a system established by the Civil Aeronautics Authority to provide a pool of civilian pilots for use during national emergencies. She also worked to disprove a 1925 [[United States Army War College|Army War College]] study which had deemed African Americans unfit to fly.<ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" /> She lobbied the federal government to award CPTP contracts to train African American pilots. In 1940, she was appointed coordinator of the Chicago units of the CPTP, and the Coffey School was selected by the U.S. Army to provide black trainees for the Air Corps pilot training program.<ref name=\"notable-black-american-women\" /> Nearly 200 students from the school went on to join the [[Tuskeegee Airmen]].<ref name=\"tuskegee-airmen\">{{cite web |title=Willa Beatrice Brown |url=http://tuskegeeairmen.org/wp-content/uploads/Willa-Brown-Bio.pdf |website=Tuskegee Airmen Inc. |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> In 1942, she attained the rank of Lieutenant in Civil Air Patrol Squadron 613-6, becoming the first African American officer in the Civil Air Patrol.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She eventually became the coordinator of war-training service for the Civil Aeronautics Authority.<ref>{{cite web |title=WILLA BROWN |url=http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |website=Hill Air Force Base |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328143509/http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |archivedate=28 Mar 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Post-aviation career ==\nIn 1946, Brown ran in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] primary elections for [[Illinois's 1st congressional district]], becoming the first African American woman to run in a congressional primary election.<ref>{{cite news |title=WILLA B. BROWN VIEWS POLITICS AS NEW CRUSADE |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=31 Mar 1946 |page=S4}}</ref> She was defeated by William E. King.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Edward |title=BUSBEY VICTORY OUTSTANDING IN CONGRESS RACES |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=11 Apr 1946 |page=2}}</ref> She ran for the same Congressional seat in the 1950 Republican primary election, and was defeated by [[Archibald Carey Jr.]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Harold |title=G. O. P. STARTS WORK TO REGAIN CONGRESS POSTS: Leaders Hail Primary Spats as Robustness |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=13 Apr 1950 |page=19}}</ref>\n\nBrown returned to teaching in high schools from 1962 until her retirement in 1971. She taught business and aeronautics.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" /> In 1972, she became the first black woman appointed to serve on the [[Federal Aviation Administration]]'s Women's Advisory Committee, a position she held for three years.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n*In 1939, Brown was cited in the 76th [[Congressional Record]] for achievements in aviation.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" />\n*In 2003, a decade after her death, Willa Beatrice Brown was inducted into the Kentucky Aviation Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"DOM\" /><ref name=\"Kentucky Women\">{{cite web | title=WILLA BEATRICE BROWN | website=Kentucky Women's History Project | date=2014-06-20 | url=http://www.kywomenshistoryproject.com/willa-beatrice-brown-2/ | access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n*In 2010, Brown was awarded the Distinguished Alumni Award by the [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania|Indiana State University]] Alumni Association.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCormick |first1=Mike |title=The amazing life of Willa Beatrice Brown |url=https://www.tribstar.com/community/the-amazing-life-of-willa-beatrice-brown/article_33082107-864e-5e6c-a533-83cadb601f43.html |website=Tribune-Star |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite web\n| last1 = Freydberg\n| first1 = Elizabeth Amelia Hadley\n| title = Aviation\n| url = http://search.credoreference.com/content/entry/rcuswh/aviation/0\n| website = Credo\n| publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company\n| accessdate = 9 September 2017\n}}\n\n*{{cite book|last1=Johnson|first1=Jesse J.|title=Black women in the Armed Forces, 1942-1974 : (a pictorial history)|date=1974|publisher=Johnson|location=Hampton, Va.|isbn=9780915044115|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Gibson|first1=Karen Bush|title=Women aviators : 26 stories of pioneer flights, daring missions, and record-setting journeys|date=2013|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, Ill.|isbn=9781613745403|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/womenaviators26s0000gibs}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-la}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kentucky Women Remembered|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Willa}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:African-American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American female military personnel]]\n[[Category:American women in World War II]]\n[[Category:Indiana State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Army]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Kentucky women aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Illinois Republicans]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American aviator, educator, activist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Willa Brown\n|image       = \"Willa Beatrice Brown, a 31-year-old Negro American, serves her country by training pilots for the U.S. Army Air Forces. - NARA - 535717.jpg\n|alt         =\n|caption     = Brown as a lieutenant in the [[United States Civil Air Patrol]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|mf=yes|1906|01|22}}\n|birth_place = [[Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1992|07|18|1906|01|22}}\n|death_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|other_names =\n|known_for   = [[Civil rights]] leader<br/>First female African American pilot licensed in the United States<br/>First African American officer in the United States Civil Air Patrol<br/>First African American woman to run for [[United States Congress]]\n|occupation  = [[Pilot (aeronautics)|Pilot]], [[Lobbyist]], [[Activist]], [[Teacher]]\n|spouse   = {{Marriage|Wilbur Hardaway|November 24, 1929|1931|div}}<br>{{Marriage|[[Cornelius Coffey]]|1939|end=div}}{{efn|Most sources give the date of their marriage as 1939, but <ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> gives the date as 1947 and indicates that there is no record of them marrying in 1939.}}<br>{{Marriage|Rev. J. H. Chappell|1955}}\n}}\n'''Willa Beatrice Brown''' (January 22, 1906 \u2013 July 18, 1992) was an American [[Pilot (aeronautics)|aviator]], [[lobbyist]], [[teacher]], and [[Civil Rights Movement|civil rights]] activist.<ref name=\"anb\">{{cite web |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |title=Brown, Willa (1906-1992), pilot and aviation educator |url=http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01864.html |website=American National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en| url-access=subscription}}</ref> She was the first [[African American]] woman to earn a pilot's license in the United States,<ref name=\"blackpast\">{{Cite web|title = Brown, Willa B. (1906\u20131992) |url = http://www.blackpast.org/aah/brown-willa-b-1906-1992|website = The Black Past|author=Davis, Edmond|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref> the first African American woman to run for the [[United States Congress]], first African American officer in the [[Civil Air Patrol]], and first woman in the U.S. to have both a pilot's license and an aircraft mechanic's license.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"DOM\"/> She was a lifelong advocate for gender and racial equality in the field of aviation as well as in the military. She not only lobbied the U.S. government to integrate the [[United States Army Air Corps]] and include African Americans in the Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), but also co-founded the [[Coffey School of Aeronautics]] with [[Cornelius Coffey]], the first private flight training academy owned and operated by African Americans in the U.S. She trained hundreds of pilots, several of whom went on to become [[Tuskegee Airmen]]; the creation of which has been credited to Brown's lobbying efforts. <ref>{{Cite web|title = Our History {{!}} 99s in Aviation History {{!}} Women in Aviation |first=Kelli|last=Grant|url = http://www.ninety-nines.org/women-in-aviation-article.htm|website = The Ninety-Nines, Inc.|access-date =February 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\">{{cite web | title=Willa Brown Chappell | website=kchr.ky.gov | date=2020-03-31 | url=https://kchr.ky.gov/ggbk/Pages/gbk33.aspx | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBrown remained politically and socially active in [[Chicago]] long after the Coffey School closed in 1945. She organized flight schools for children, ran in Congressional primary elections in 1946 and 1950, was an active member of the Westside Community Church, and taught in the Chicago Public School System until 1971, when she retired at age 65.\n\n== Early life ==\nWilla Beatrice Brown was born to Reverend and Mrs. Erice B. Brown on January 22, 1906, in [[Glasgow, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"blackpast\"/> She graduated from Wiley High School in Terra Haute, Indiana, and attended [[Indiana State University|Indiana State Teachers College]] where she graduated in 1927 with a bachelor's degree. Ten years later she earned an [[M.B.A.]] from [[Northwestern University]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Black Women in America: An Historical Encyclopedia|year=1994|publisher=Indiana University Press | location= Bloomington |isbn=0-253-32774-1 | pages=184\u2013185 | chapter=Brown, Willa Beatrice (1906\u20131992)|first=Elizabeth Hadley|last=Freydberg}}</ref><ref name=\"Davis 2012\">{{cite web | last=Davis | first=Edmond | title=Willa B. Brown (1906-1992) | website=BlackPast | date=2012-07-25 | url=https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/brown-willa-b-1906-1992/ | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBrown taught in [[Gary, Indiana]] at [[Emerson High School (Indiana)|Emerson High School]]'s [[Theodore Roosevelt College and Career Academy#History|Roosevelt Annex]] from 1927 to 1932.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/><ref name=\"Davis 2012\"/> She then moved to [[Chicago]], where she worked in a variety of jobs, including secretarial work, social work, and teaching.<ref name=\"notable-black-american-women\">{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Jessie Carney |title=Notable Black American women |publisher=Gale Research |isbn=978-0810391772 |pages=69\u201371}}</ref> In 1934, she met [[John C. Robinson]], who introduced her to the Challenger Air Pilots Association, a group of African American pilots.<ref name=\"anb\" />\n\n== Aviation career ==\n[[File:Young Willa Brown.jpg|thumb|left|Willa Brown as a young woman, standing on an airfield]]\nIn 1934, Brown began studying at Chicago's racially segregated Harlem Field with [[Cornelius Coffey]], a certified flight instructor and expert aviation mechanic. She was one of few women who attended [[Curtiss\u2013Wright Aeronautical University]] where she studied aircraft maintenance and earned an aircraft mechanic's license in 1935.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\">{{cite book |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |last2=Sawyer |first2=Miriam |last3=Fannin |first3=Caroline |title=Distinguished African Americans in aviation and space science |publisher=Oryx Press |isbn=978-1573562461 |pages=49\u201352|location=Westport, Conn.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/distinguishedafr00gube}}</ref><ref name=\"DOM\">{{cite web | title=Masterful Willa Brown (1906-1992) | website=DOM Magazine | date=2010-01-01 | url=https://dommagazine.com/article/masterful-willa-brown-1906-1992 | access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> She earned a private pilot's license in 1938<ref>{{cite news |title=YOUNG WOMAN FLYER GETS PILOT'S LICENSE: Willa Brown, Chicago Aviatrix, Can Carry Passengers, Give Instructions or Make Cross-Country Flights |work=The Pittsburgh Courier |date=2 July 1938 |page=11}}</ref> and a commercial pilot's license in 1939, becoming the first African American woman to earn either type of license in the United States.<ref name=\"anb\" /><ref name=\"chicago-tribune\">{{cite news |title=Chicago and the Tuskegee Airmen |work=Chicago Tribune |date=January 19, 2015 | location=Sec. 1 |page=14 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/opinion/editorials/ct-tuskegee-airmen-chicago-world-war-ii-willa-brown-edit-0119-jm-20150119-story.html}}</ref>{{efn|[[Bessie Coleman]] was the first black American, male or female, to earn an international pilot's license which she obtained in France in the 1920s, whereas Brown was the first black American woman to earn a pilot's license in the U.S.; see <ref name=DOM/>, <ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\" />, <ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" /> and <ref name=\"Dawson Bowles 2005 p. 5\">{{cite book | last=Dawson | first=V.P. | last2=Bowles | first2=M.D. | title=Realizing the Dream of Flight: Biographical Essays in Honor of the Centennial of Flight, 1903-2003 | publisher=National Aeronautics and Space Administration, NASA History Division, Office of External Relations | series=NASA SP | year=2005 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NpIpJI7nYV4C&pg=PA5 | access-date=2020-04-05 | page=5}}</ref>}}\n\nWilla Brown, Cornelius Coffey and Enoch P. Waters worked together to form the National Negro Airmen Association of America, later renamed to National Airmen's Association of America which was incorporated in 1939. Their primary mission was to attract more interest in aviation, help develop a better understanding in the field of aeronautics and pursue more African American participation in both fields.<ref name=\"Lest We Forget 1939\">{{cite web | title=NATIONAL AIRMEN ASSOCIATION OF AMERICA ...before the Tuskegee Airmen :: World War II :: Tuskegee Airmen :: Lest We Forget | website=Lest We Forget | date=1939-08-16 | url=http://lestweforget.hamptonu.edu/page.cfm?uuid=9FEC42B7-EB34-45CE-CC673CA72120E420 | access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> As the organization's national secretary and president of the Chicago branch, Brown became an activist for racial equality. Later, she and Coffey married and established the Coffey School of Aeronautics at Harlem Airport in Chicago, where they trained black pilots and aviation mechanics.<ref name=\"cap-bio\">{{cite web |last1=Montague |first1=Carlos |title=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |url=https://www.cap.news/willa-brown-pioneer-for-female--african-american-aviation/ |website=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n[[File:LIEUT. WILLA BROWN - AVIATRIX-MAKER OF PILOTS - NARA - 535627.tif|thumb|Office for Emergency Management publication featuring Brown]]\nShe lobbied the government continuously, advocating for integration of black pilots into a then-segregated Army Air Corps and federal [[Civilian Pilot Training Program]] (CPTP), the latter of which was a system established by the Civil Aeronautics Authority to provide a pool of civilian pilots for use during national emergencies. She also worked to disprove a 1925 [[United States Army War College|Army War College]] study which had deemed African Americans unfit to fly.<ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" /> She lobbied the federal government to award CPTP contracts to train African American pilots. In 1940, she was appointed coordinator of the Chicago units of the CPTP, and the Coffey School was selected by the U.S. Army to provide black trainees for the Air Corps pilot training program.<ref name=\"notable-black-american-women\" /> Nearly 200 students from the school went on to join the [[Tuskeegee Airmen]].<ref name=\"tuskegee-airmen\">{{cite web |title=Willa Beatrice Brown |url=http://tuskegeeairmen.org/wp-content/uploads/Willa-Brown-Bio.pdf |website=Tuskegee Airmen Inc. |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> In 1942, she attained the rank of Lieutenant in Civil Air Patrol Squadron 613-6, becoming the first African American officer in the Civil Air Patrol.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She eventually became the coordinator of war-training service for the Civil Aeronautics Authority.<ref>{{cite web |title=WILLA BROWN |url=http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |website=Hill Air Force Base |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328143509/http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |archivedate=28 Mar 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Post-aviation career ==\nIn 1946, Brown ran in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] primary elections for [[Illinois's 1st congressional district]], becoming the first African American woman to run in a congressional primary election.<ref>{{cite news |title=WILLA B. BROWN VIEWS POLITICS AS NEW CRUSADE |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=31 Mar 1946 |page=S4}}</ref> She was defeated by William E. King.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Edward |title=BUSBEY VICTORY OUTSTANDING IN CONGRESS RACES |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=11 Apr 1946 |page=2}}</ref> She ran for the same Congressional seat in the 1950 Republican primary election, and was defeated by [[Archibald Carey Jr.]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Harold |title=G. O. P. STARTS WORK TO REGAIN CONGRESS POSTS: Leaders Hail Primary Spats as Robustness |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=13 Apr 1950 |page=19}}</ref>\n\nBrown returned to teaching in high schools from 1962 until her retirement in 1971. She taught business and aeronautics.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" /> In 1972, she became the first black woman appointed to serve on the [[Federal Aviation Administration]]'s Women's Advisory Committee, a position she held for three years.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n*In 1939, Brown was cited in the 76th [[Congressional Record]] for achievements in aviation.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" />\n*In 2003, a decade after her death, Willa Beatrice Brown was inducted into the Kentucky Aviation Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"DOM\" /><ref name=\"Kentucky Women\">{{cite web | title=WILLA BEATRICE BROWN | website=Kentucky Women's History Project | date=2014-06-20 | url=http://www.kywomenshistoryproject.com/willa-beatrice-brown-2/ | access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n*In 2010, Brown was awarded the Distinguished Alumni Award by the [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania|Indiana State University]] Alumni Association.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCormick |first1=Mike |title=The amazing life of Willa Beatrice Brown |url=https://www.tribstar.com/community/the-amazing-life-of-willa-beatrice-brown/article_33082107-864e-5e6c-a533-83cadb601f43.html |website=Tribune-Star |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite web\n| last1 = Freydberg\n| first1 = Elizabeth Amelia Hadley\n| title = Aviation\n| url = http://search.credoreference.com/content/entry/rcuswh/aviation/0\n| website = Credo\n| publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company\n| accessdate = 9 September 2017\n}}\n\n*{{cite book|last1=Johnson|first1=Jesse J.|title=Black women in the Armed Forces, 1942-1974 : (a pictorial history)|date=1974|publisher=Johnson|location=Hampton, Va.|isbn=9780915044115|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Gibson|first1=Karen Bush|title=Women aviators : 26 stories of pioneer flights, daring missions, and record-setting journeys|date=2013|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, Ill.|isbn=9781613745403|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/womenaviators26s0000gibs}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-la}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kentucky Women Remembered|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Willa}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n