{"title_page": "Metro Balderas", "text_new": "{{For|the song|Metro Balderas (song)}}\n{{short description|Mexico City metro station}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name            = [[File:Metro Balderas pictogram.svg|25px]] Balderas\n| style           = Mexico City Metro\n| style2          = 1 3\n| type            = [[Mexico City Metro|STC]] [[rapid transit]]\n| image           = Metro Balderas 2019.jpg\n| image_caption   = A NE-92 arriving to Line 1 platforms.\n| address         = [[Colonia Doctores]], [[Cuauht\u00e9moc, Mexico City|Cuauht\u00e9moc]]\n| borough         = [[Mexico City]]\n| country         = Mexico\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|19.42744|N|99.149036|W|region:MX-DIF_type:railwaystation|display=it}}\n| elevation       = \n| other           = [[File:Mexico City Metrob\u00fas Line 3 icon.svg|16px|link=Mexico City Metrob\u00fas Line 3]]\n| structure       = Underground\n| platform        = 4 side platforms\n| depth           = \n| levels          = 2\n| tracks          = 4\n| parking         = No\n| bicycle         = No\n| opened          = {{rint|mexicocity|1}} 4 September 1969<br>{{rint|mexicocity|3}} 20 November 1970\n| closed          = \n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = \n| ADA             = Yes\n| code            = \n| owned           = [[Mexico City Metro|STC]]\n| operator        = [[Mexico City Metro|STC]]\n| former          = \n| passengers      = 30,322 per day (2017)<ref>{{cite web|title=Afluencia de estaci\u00f3n por l\u00ednea 2017|url=https://metro.cdmx.gob.mx/operacion/mas-informacion/afluencia-de-estacion-por-linea/afluencia-de-estacion-por-linea-2017|publisher=Metro CDMX|access-date=24 February 2019}}</ref>\n| pass_percent    = \n| pass_system     = \n| mpassengers     = \n| services        = {{Adjacent stations|system=Mexico City Metro\n|line1=1|left1=Cuauht\u00e9moc|right1=Salto del Agua\n|line3=3|left3=Ju\u00e1rez|right3=Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes}}\n| map_locator     = \n}}\n'''Metro Balderas'''  is an underground [[metro station|station]] on the [[Mexico City Metro]].<ref name=\"metro\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.metro.df.gob.mx/red/estacion.html?id=13|title=Balderas|language=Spanish|accessdate=1 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805205127/http://www.metro.df.gob.mx/red/estacion.html?id=13|archivedate=5 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"archambault\">{{Cite web|last=Archambault|first=Richard|url=http://mexicometro.org/metro/line1/balderas/|title=Balderas (Line 1) &raquo;  Mexico City Metro System|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> It is located in the [[Cuauht\u00e9moc, D.F.|Cuauht\u00e9moc]] borough in the center of [[Mexico City]].<ref name=\"metro\"/> It is a transfer station along [[Mexico City Metro Line 1|Lines 1]] and [[Mexico City Metro Line 3|3]].<ref name=\"metro\"/><ref name=\"archambault_line3\">{{Cite web|last=Archambault|first=Richard|url=http://mexicometro.org/metro/line3/balderas/|title=Balderas (Line 3)&raquo;  Mexico City Metro System|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Name and iconography==\nThe station receives its name from the nearby Balderas street, which in turn was named in honor of [[Lucas Balderas]], a Mexican military officer that participated in the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] and was killed at the [[Battle of Molino del Rey]] in 1847. It is said that his last words were \"poor country of mine\".<ref>{{cite news|title=\u00bfSabes por qu\u00e9 el logotipo de la estaci\u00f3n Balderas es un ca\u00f1\u00f3n?|url=https://www.excelsior.com.mx/comunidad/2016/05/09/1091580|newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=9 May 2016|access-date=18 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lucas Balderas|url=http://www.durangomas.mx/2013/09/lucas-balderas/|website=www.durangomas.mx|access-date=18 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe station pictogram depicts the [[Viceroyalty of New Spain|colonial-era]] [[cannon]] preserved on the nearby Plaza de La Ciudadela.<ref name=\"metro\"/><ref name=\"archambault\"/> The cannon is a reminder of the [[Ten Tragic Days]], which was a period a little bit longer than 10 days in which a coup the democratically elected government of [[Francisco I. Madero]] took place. This chapter would end with the murder of  President Madero and Vice-President [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Pino Su\u00e1rez]], as well as the rise to the presidency of [[Victoriano Huerta]].<ref name=\"metro\"/>\n\n==General information==\nNearby Metro Balderas are some interesting places, like La Ciudadela market, filled with Mexican handicrafts,<ref name=\"ciudela_times\">{{Cite web|url=http://travel.nytimes.com/travel/guides/north-america/mexico/mexico-city/31159/mercado-de-la-ciudadela/shopping-detail.html|title=Mercado de La Ciudadela|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=1 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930212601/http://travel.nytimes.com/travel/guides/north-america/mexico/mexico-city/31159/mercado-de-la-ciudadela/shopping-detail.html|archivedate=30 September 2012}}</ref> the [[Jos\u00e9 Vasconcelos Central Library of Mexico City]],<ref name=\"vasconcelos\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bibliotecavasconcelos.gob.mx/|title=Biblioteca Vasconcelos|language=Spanish|accessdate=1 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702020851/http://www.bibliotecavasconcelos.gob.mx/|archive-date=2 July 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>  and facilities of broadcaster [[Televisa]]. Next to the library lies a ''[[tianguis]]'' (street market) full of books old and new, comics, collectibles, etc.\n\nThis station has an information desk and facilities for the [[disabled]].<ref name=\"metro\"/>  It also displays a plaque unveiled on 19 September 2004, celebrating Mexican [[rock musician]] [[Rockdrigo Gonz\u00e1lez]], killed exactly 19 years earlier in the [[1985 Mexico City earthquake]] and composer of a song titled \"[[Metro Balderas (song)|Metro Balderas]]\". On September 2011 a real-size bronze statue of Rockdrigo was also unveiled inside the station.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rockdrigo 'cantar\u00e1' permanentemente en el metro Balderas del DF|url=https://expansion.mx/entretenimiento/2011/09/19/rockdrigo-cantara-permanentemente-en-el-metro-balderas-del-df|publisher=Expansi\u00f3n|date=19 September 2011|access-date=24 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nAlthough this station is totally underground, [[cellular phone]] signals ([[GSM]] and [[Time division multiple access|TDMA]] for several providers) are able to reach the platform. The station also has charging stations for mobile devices.<ref>{{cite news|title=Instalan en Metro Balderas centros de carga para celulares|url=https://www.diariodemexico.com/instalan-en-metro-balderas-centros-de-carga-para-celulares-0|newspaper=Diario de M\u00e9xico|date=15 August 2017|access-date=24 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nMetro Balderas was opened on 4 September 1969, as part of  the first stage of [[Mexico City Metro Line 1|Line 1]], going from [[Metro Chapultepec|Chapultepec]] to [[Metro Zaragoza|Zaragoza]].<ref name=MetroCDMX>{{cite web|title=Balderas|url=https://www.metro.cdmx.gob.mx/la-red/linea-1/balderas|publisher=Metro CDMX|access-date=18 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe station became the [[Mexico City Metro|network's]] second transfer station, when the first stretch of [[Mexico City Metro Line 3|Line 3]], from [[Metro Tlatelolco|Tlatelolco]] to [[Metro Hospital General|Hospital General]], was opened in November 1970.<ref name=MetroCDMX></ref>\n\n===Incidents===\nOn Friday, 18 September 2009 a shooting occurred on the platform. A man was tagging one of the station walls with a marker, therefore, he was confronted by a police officer. He reacted by taking out a gun and killing him and a construction worker, who tried to disarm him, leaving also five wounded.<ref name=\"avila\">{{Cite news|last=Avila|first=Eduardo|title=Mexico: Shooting at Balderas Metro Station |work=[[Global Voices Online]]|date=20 September 2009}}</ref> The man later claimed that he committed the killings \"in the name of god\" and was sentenced to 151 years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=El d\u00eda en que el Metro Balderas se ti\u00f1\u00f3 de rojo|url=https://www.reporteindigo.com/reporte/el-dia-en-el-que-el-metro-balderas-se-tino-de-rojo/|newspaper=[[Reporte Indigo]]|date=18 September 2018|access-date=18 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 December 2018, a woman gave birth to a child inside the station, at the Line 1 platforms, helped by personnel of the [[Mexican Red Cross]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Nace un beb\u00e9 en la estaci\u00f3n Balderas del Metro de la CDMX|url=https://noticieros.televisa.com/ultimas-noticias/nace-bebe-estacion-balderas-metro-cdmx/|publisher=Noticieros Televisa|date=29 December 2018|access-date=18 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==Nearby==\n*Biblioteca de M\u00e9xico, public library.\n*[[Escuela Libre de Derecho]], law school.\n*[[Televisa]] Chapultepec headquarters.\n*Parque Tols\u00e1, park.\n*Centro Escolar Revoluci\u00f3n, elementary school.\n\n==Exits==\n===Line 1===\n*North: Tols\u00e1 street and Balderas, [[Historic center of Mexico City|Centro]]\n*South: Avenida Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes and Avenida Chapultepec, [[Colonia Doctores]]\n\n===Line 3===\n*East: Avenida Arcos de Bel\u00e9n, [[Colonia Doctores]]\n*Southeast: Avenida Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes and Dr. R\u00edo de la Loza street, [[Colonia Doctores]]\n\n==Station layout==\n\n{| border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''G'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=200 valign=top|Street Level\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=200 valign=top|Exit/Entrance\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''B1'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=200 valign=top|Mezzanine for platform connection\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=200 valign=top|Fare control/Ticket windows\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 rowspan=4 valign=top|\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=100|'''Westbound'''\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=390|\u2190 {{rint|mexicocity|mcm}} {{rint|mexicocity|1}} toward [[Metro Observatorio|Observatorio]] {{small|([[Metro Cuauht\u00e9moc|Cuauht\u00e9moc]])}}\n|-\n|'''Eastbound'''\n|{{0|\u2192}} {{rint|mexicocity|mcm}} {{rint|mexicocity|1}} toward [[Metro Pantitl\u00e1n|Pantitl\u00e1n]] {{small|([[Metro Salto del Agua|Salto del Agua]])}} \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 rowspan=4 valign=top|'''B2'''\n|style=\"border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=100|'''Northbound'''\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=390|\u2190 {{rint|mexicocity|mcm}} {{rint|mexicocity|3}} toward [[Metro Indios Verdes|Indios Verdes]] {{small|([[Metro Ju\u00e1rez|Ju\u00e1rez]])}}\n|-\n|'''Southbound'''\n|{{0|\u2192}} {{rint|mexicocity|mcm}} {{rint|mexicocity|3}} toward [[Metro Universidad|Universidad]] {{small|([[Metro Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes|Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes]])}} \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right}}\n|}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Metro_Balderas_02.jpg|Entrance to the station in the corner of [[Avenida Chapultepec]] and Av. Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes\nImage:Metro_Balderas_01.jpg|Entrance sign to the station\nImage:Metro Balderas Line 3 Platforms.jpg|Line 3 platforms\nImage:Commemorative plaque to Rodrigo Gonzalez.JPG|Commemorative plaque to [[Rockdrigo Gonz\u00e1lez]]\nImage:Estatua_a_Rodrigo_Gonz\u00e1lez_(m\u00fasico_mexicano)_Aka_\"Rockdrigo\".jpg|Statue honoring [[Rockdrigo Gonz\u00e1lez|Rockdrigo]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commonscat-inline|Balderas (station)}}\n{{Cuauht\u00e9moc, Mexico City}}\n{{MxMetro}}\n\n[[Category:Mexico City metro stations|Balderas]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1969]]\n[[Category:1969 establishments in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1970]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the song|Metro Balderas (song)}}\n{{short description|Mexico City metro station}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name            = [[File:Metro Balderas pictogram.svg|25px]] Balderas\n| style           = Mexico City Metro\n| style2          = 1 3\n| type            = [[Mexico City Metro|STC]] [[rapid transit]]\n| image           = Metro Balderas 2019.jpg\n| image_caption   = A NE-92 arriving to Line 1 platforms.\n| address         = [[Colonia Doctores]], [[Cuauht\u00e9moc, Mexico City|Cuauht\u00e9moc]]\n| borough         = [[Mexico City]]\n| country         = Mexico\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|19.42744|N|99.149036|W|region:MX-DIF_type:railwaystation|display=it}}\n| elevation       = \n| other           = [[File:Mexico City Metrob\u00fas Line 3 icon.svg|18px|link=Mexico City Metrob\u00fas Line 3]]\n| structure       = Underground\n| platform        = 4 side platforms\n| depth           = \n| levels          = 2\n| tracks          = 4\n| parking         = No\n| bicycle         = No\n| opened          = {{rint|mexicocity|1}} 4 September 1969<br>{{rint|mexicocity|3}} 20 November 1970\n| closed          = \n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = \n| ADA             = Yes\n| code            = \n| owned           = [[Mexico City Metro|STC]]\n| operator        = [[Mexico City Metro|STC]]\n| former          = \n| passengers      = 30,322 per day (2017)<ref>{{cite web|title=Afluencia de estaci\u00f3n por l\u00ednea 2017|url=https://metro.cdmx.gob.mx/operacion/mas-informacion/afluencia-de-estacion-por-linea/afluencia-de-estacion-por-linea-2017|publisher=Metro CDMX|access-date=24 February 2019}}</ref>\n| pass_percent    = \n| pass_system     = \n| mpassengers     = \n| services        = {{Adjacent stations|system=Mexico City Metro\n|line1=1|left1=Cuauht\u00e9moc|right1=Salto del Agua\n|line3=3|left3=Ju\u00e1rez|right3=Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes}}\n| map_locator     = \n}}\n'''Metro Balderas'''  is an underground [[metro station|station]] on the [[Mexico City Metro]].<ref name=\"metro\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.metro.df.gob.mx/red/estacion.html?id=13|title=Balderas|language=Spanish|accessdate=1 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805205127/http://www.metro.df.gob.mx/red/estacion.html?id=13|archivedate=5 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"archambault\">{{Cite web|last=Archambault|first=Richard|url=http://mexicometro.org/metro/line1/balderas/|title=Balderas (Line 1) &raquo;  Mexico City Metro System|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref> It is located in the [[Cuauht\u00e9moc, D.F.|Cuauht\u00e9moc]] borough in the center of [[Mexico City]].<ref name=\"metro\"/> It is a transfer station along [[Mexico City Metro Line 1|Lines 1]] and [[Mexico City Metro Line 3|3]].<ref name=\"metro\"/><ref name=\"archambault_line3\">{{Cite web|last=Archambault|first=Richard|url=http://mexicometro.org/metro/line3/balderas/|title=Balderas (Line 3)&raquo;  Mexico City Metro System|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Name and iconography==\nThe station receives its name from the nearby Balderas street, which in turn was named in honor of [[Lucas Balderas]], a Mexican military officer that participated in the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] and was killed at the [[Battle of Molino del Rey]] in 1847. It is said that his last words were \"poor country of mine\".<ref>{{cite news|title=\u00bfSabes por qu\u00e9 el logotipo de la estaci\u00f3n Balderas es un ca\u00f1\u00f3n?|url=https://www.excelsior.com.mx/comunidad/2016/05/09/1091580|newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=9 May 2016|access-date=18 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lucas Balderas|url=http://www.durangomas.mx/2013/09/lucas-balderas/|website=www.durangomas.mx|access-date=18 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe station pictogram depicts the [[Viceroyalty of New Spain|colonial-era]] [[cannon]] preserved on the nearby Plaza de La Ciudadela.<ref name=\"metro\"/><ref name=\"archambault\"/> The cannon is a reminder of the [[Ten Tragic Days]], which was a period a little bit longer than 10 days in which a coup the democratically elected government of [[Francisco I. Madero]] took place. This chapter would end with the murder of  President Madero and Vice-President [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Pino Su\u00e1rez]], as well as the rise to the presidency of [[Victoriano Huerta]].<ref name=\"metro\"/>\n\n==General information==\nNearby Metro Balderas are some interesting places, like La Ciudadela market, filled with Mexican handicrafts,<ref name=\"ciudela_times\">{{Cite web|url=http://travel.nytimes.com/travel/guides/north-america/mexico/mexico-city/31159/mercado-de-la-ciudadela/shopping-detail.html|title=Mercado de La Ciudadela|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=1 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930212601/http://travel.nytimes.com/travel/guides/north-america/mexico/mexico-city/31159/mercado-de-la-ciudadela/shopping-detail.html|archivedate=30 September 2012}}</ref> the [[Jos\u00e9 Vasconcelos Central Library of Mexico City]],<ref name=\"vasconcelos\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bibliotecavasconcelos.gob.mx/|title=Biblioteca Vasconcelos|language=Spanish|accessdate=1 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702020851/http://www.bibliotecavasconcelos.gob.mx/|archive-date=2 July 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>  and facilities of broadcaster [[Televisa]]. Next to the library lies a ''[[tianguis]]'' (street market) full of books old and new, comics, collectibles, etc.\n\nThis station has an information desk and facilities for the [[disabled]].<ref name=\"metro\"/>  It also displays a plaque unveiled on 19 September 2004, celebrating Mexican [[rock musician]] [[Rockdrigo Gonz\u00e1lez]], killed exactly 19 years earlier in the [[1985 Mexico City earthquake]] and composer of a song titled \"[[Metro Balderas (song)|Metro Balderas]]\". On September 2011 a real-size bronze statue of Rockdrigo was also unveiled inside the station.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rockdrigo 'cantar\u00e1' permanentemente en el metro Balderas del DF|url=https://expansion.mx/entretenimiento/2011/09/19/rockdrigo-cantara-permanentemente-en-el-metro-balderas-del-df|publisher=Expansi\u00f3n|date=19 September 2011|access-date=24 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nAlthough this station is totally underground, [[cellular phone]] signals ([[GSM]] and [[Time division multiple access|TDMA]] for several providers) are able to reach the platform. The station also has charging stations for mobile devices.<ref>{{cite news|title=Instalan en Metro Balderas centros de carga para celulares|url=https://www.diariodemexico.com/instalan-en-metro-balderas-centros-de-carga-para-celulares-0|newspaper=Diario de M\u00e9xico|date=15 August 2017|access-date=24 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nMetro Balderas was opened on 4 September 1969, as part of  the first stage of [[Mexico City Metro Line 1|Line 1]], going from [[Metro Chapultepec|Chapultepec]] to [[Metro Zaragoza|Zaragoza]].<ref name=MetroCDMX>{{cite web|title=Balderas|url=https://www.metro.cdmx.gob.mx/la-red/linea-1/balderas|publisher=Metro CDMX|access-date=18 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe station became the [[Mexico City Metro|network's]] second transfer station, when the first stretch of [[Mexico City Metro Line 3|Line 3]], from [[Metro Tlatelolco|Tlatelolco]] to [[Metro Hospital General|Hospital General]], was opened in November 1970.<ref name=MetroCDMX></ref>\n\n===Incidents===\nOn Friday, 18 September 2009 a shooting occurred on the platform. A man was tagging one of the station walls with a marker, therefore, he was confronted by a police officer. He reacted by taking out a gun and killing him and a construction worker, who tried to disarm him, leaving also five wounded.<ref name=\"avila\">{{Cite news|last=Avila|first=Eduardo|title=Mexico: Shooting at Balderas Metro Station |work=[[Global Voices Online]]|date=20 September 2009}}</ref> The man later claimed that he committed the killings \"in the name of god\" and was sentenced to 151 years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=El d\u00eda en que el Metro Balderas se ti\u00f1\u00f3 de rojo|url=https://www.reporteindigo.com/reporte/el-dia-en-el-que-el-metro-balderas-se-tino-de-rojo/|newspaper=[[Reporte Indigo]]|date=18 September 2018|access-date=18 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 December 2018, a woman gave birth to a child inside the station, at the Line 1 platforms, helped by personnel of the [[Mexican Red Cross]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Nace un beb\u00e9 en la estaci\u00f3n Balderas del Metro de la CDMX|url=https://noticieros.televisa.com/ultimas-noticias/nace-bebe-estacion-balderas-metro-cdmx/|publisher=Noticieros Televisa|date=29 December 2018|access-date=18 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==Nearby==\n*Biblioteca de M\u00e9xico, public library.\n*[[Escuela Libre de Derecho]], law school.\n*[[Televisa]] Chapultepec headquarters.\n*Parque Tols\u00e1, park.\n*Centro Escolar Revoluci\u00f3n, elementary school.\n\n==Exits==\n===Line 1===\n*North: Tols\u00e1 street and Balderas, [[Historic center of Mexico City|Centro]]\n*South: Avenida Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes and Avenida Chapultepec, [[Colonia Doctores]]\n\n===Line 3===\n*East: Avenida Arcos de Bel\u00e9n, [[Colonia Doctores]]\n*Southeast: Avenida Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes and Dr. R\u00edo de la Loza street, [[Colonia Doctores]]\n\n==Station layout==\n\n{| border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''G'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=200 valign=top|Street Level\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=200 valign=top|Exit/Entrance\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''B1'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=200 valign=top|Mezzanine for platform connection\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=200 valign=top|Fare control/Ticket windows\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 rowspan=4 valign=top|\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=100|'''Westbound'''\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=390|\u2190 {{rint|mexicocity|mcm}} {{rint|mexicocity|1}} toward [[Metro Observatorio|Observatorio]] {{small|([[Metro Cuauht\u00e9moc|Cuauht\u00e9moc]])}}\n|-\n|'''Eastbound'''\n|{{0|\u2192}} {{rint|mexicocity|mcm}} {{rint|mexicocity|1}} toward [[Metro Pantitl\u00e1n|Pantitl\u00e1n]] {{small|([[Metro Salto del Agua|Salto del Agua]])}} \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 rowspan=4 valign=top|'''B2'''\n|style=\"border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right}}\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=100|'''Northbound'''\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=390|\u2190 {{rint|mexicocity|mcm}} {{rint|mexicocity|3}} toward [[Metro Indios Verdes|Indios Verdes]] {{small|([[Metro Ju\u00e1rez|Ju\u00e1rez]])}}\n|-\n|'''Southbound'''\n|{{0|\u2192}} {{rint|mexicocity|mcm}} {{rint|mexicocity|3}} toward [[Metro Universidad|Universidad]] {{small|([[Metro Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes|Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes]])}} \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|{{small|[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right}}\n|}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Metro_Balderas_02.jpg|Entrance to the station in the corner of [[Avenida Chapultepec]] and Av. Ni\u00f1os H\u00e9roes\nImage:Metro_Balderas_01.jpg|Entrance sign to the station\nImage:Metro Balderas Line 3 Platforms.jpg|Line 3 platforms\nImage:Commemorative plaque to Rodrigo Gonzalez.JPG|Commemorative plaque to [[Rockdrigo Gonz\u00e1lez]]\nImage:Estatua_a_Rodrigo_Gonz\u00e1lez_(m\u00fasico_mexicano)_Aka_\"Rockdrigo\".jpg|Statue honoring [[Rockdrigo Gonz\u00e1lez|Rockdrigo]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commonscat-inline|Balderas (station)}}\n{{Cuauht\u00e9moc, Mexico City}}\n{{MxMetro}}\n\n[[Category:Mexico City metro stations|Balderas]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1969]]\n[[Category:1969 establishments in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1970]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "Cocu15", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metro_Balderas"}
{"title_page": "Washington Redskins Marching Band", "text_new": "{{short description|Official marching band for the Washington Redskins}}\n{{Distinguish|The Redskins}}\n[[File:Fairfax July 4th QD3J0123 (28052788571).jpg|thumb|Washington Redskins Marching Band banner]]\n[[File:Fairfax July 4th QD3J0125 (28052792821).jpg|thumb|Washington Redskins Marching Band at 4th of July parade in Fairfax, Virginia]]\n\nThe '''Washington Redskins Marching Band''' or '''Redskins Band''' is the official marching band for the [[Washington Redskins]]  founded in 1937.<ref name=NPR-2010>{{cite news|last1=Akins|first1=Robert, III|title=The Real Twelfth Man: On The Field With The NFL's Oldest Marching Band|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2010/11/15/131331163/the-real-twelfth-man-on-the-field-with-football-s-oldest-marching-band|accessdate=6 July 2015|work=The Record|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|date=15 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=Halftime>{{cite news|last1=Carden|first1=Eddie|title=Are You Ready for Some Football ... er, Marching Band?|url=http://halftimemag.com/articles/11-2007/11-2007-features/are-you-ready-for-some-football.html|accessdate=6 July 2015|publisher=[[Halftime Magazine]]|date=November 2007}}</ref>  They are the oldest marching band of the [[National Football League]].<ref name=NPR-2010/>  They are most noted for performing ''[[Hail to the Redskins]]'' after each score by the Redskins at home games.<ref name=snider>{{cite book|last1=Snider|first1=Rick|title=100 Things Redskins Fans Should Know & Do Before They Die|date=2014|publisher=Triumph Books LLC|location=[[Chicago, Illinois]]|page=202|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XQ1MBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA202&dq=%22The%20Redskins%20Band%22%20-wikipedia&pg=PA203#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=6 July 2015|isbn=9781623689735}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.redskins.com/stadium/marching-band}}\n\n{{Washington Redskins}}\n\n[[Category:Washington Redskins]]\n[[